<HEADLINE> EU Foreign Ministers Look to Union's Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
THE HAGUE, May 20 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers of the 15
member countries of the European Union (EU) met here on Tuesday to
discuss reforms of European institutions and prepare for the
informal EU summit scheduled for Friday in the Dutch seaside town
of Noordwijk.
</P>
<P>
The ministers are to focus on topics such as the composition of
the European Commission, the EU's executive body, and the role of
the European Parliament, said Dutch government officials, whose
country at present holds EU's rotating six-month presidency.
</P>
<P>
The meeting in The Hague is the second phase of talks this week
on revising the union's Maastricht Treaty.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday and Saturday, Dutch Foreign Secretary Michiel
Patijn convened personal representatives of the 15 foreign
ministers in Maastricht in an informal session, and discussed the
responsibilities of the bloc to combat unemployment it faces.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, Patijn also proposed giving Britain and Ireland
special status in the Schengen agreement, which aims to eliminate
internal borders between most EU members.
</P>
<P>
The third step in the negotiations follows on Friday in
Noordwijk, where heads of EU states will attend the extraordinary
European Council.
</P>
<P>
The leaders are expected to furnish political guidelines on
issues such as defense and institutional reforms.
</P>
<P>
Only after these consultations, diplomats said, would the Dutch
presidency present the draft texts of the revised EU treaty,
produced during the Inter-Governmental Conference (IGC) which
began last March.
</P>
<P>
This would be shortly before the EU's Summit on June 16-17 in
Amsterdam, a landmark meeting in which the EU was to prepare for
its planned enlargement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
