<HEADLINE> Sinn Fein to Hold Meeting with British Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 20 (Xinhua) -- The Irish Republican Army's
political wing, Sinn Fein, is expected to meet British officials
on Wednesday to push forward the Northern Ireland peace process.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein and Labor government officials will meet in the
Northern Ireland capital of Belfast, the first such talks since
the IRA ended its 17-month ceasefire in February last year and
relaunched terrorist actions on the British mainland.
</P>
<P>
The talks were possible after British Prime Minister Tony
Blair, who came to power early this month after the May 1
election, eased a ban last week on official contacts with Sinn
Fein in a bid to put new life to the deadlocked peace process.
</P>
<P>
The IRA has been fighting against the British rule in Northern
Ireland for the past 28 years. Both Britain and Ireland banned
official contacts with Sinn Fein after the IRA quit the truce last
year.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein's delegation was likely to be led by Martin
McGuinness, its chief negotiator, who won a seat in the British
parliament along with party president Gerry Adams in the elections.
</P>
<P>
Later this week Britain's Northern Ireland Secretary, Mo
Mowlam, will visit Washington for discussions with United States
government officials about giving the peace process in Northern
Ireland a new start.
</P>
<P>
Northern Ireland's 60 percent Protestant majority want to stay
British, but the 40 percent Roman Catholics, some of whom support
the IRA, want to merge with Ireland in a united country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
