<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak Calls for Bigger EU Role in Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 20 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak today called on the European Union (EU) to play a bigger
role alongside the United States to help revitalize the Middle
East peace process, the German Foreign Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
During talks with German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel, Mubarak
said he was worried and becoming increasingly disappointed over
the deadlock in the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
He said the resumption of constructive talks over peace in the
Middle East was possible only after Israel stopped building Jewish
settlements in Palestinian areas.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the German business daily, Das
Handelsblatt, (Tuesday issue), Mubarak said Israel should suspend
its Jewish house project at least until the start of negotiations
on the permanent status of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Both the Israelis and the Palestinians claim Jerusalem is their
capital.
</P>
<P>
"The problem now is Jerusalem and it gives us a lot of
headaches. If the Israelis were willing to suspend the
construction of settlements until the start of negotiations on
Jerusalem, maybe for six months, things could look quite
different," Mubarak said.
</P>
<P>
He also told the German newspaper that he was deeply
disappointed with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu who,
as he said, only paid lip service to the implementation of the
Oslo agreement.
</P>
<P>
"Israel must fulfill the agreements reached by Netanyahu's
predecessors, Yitzhak Rabin and Shimon Peres," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that we can still find a solution to the current
situation in order to bring new movement into the peace process,"
Mubarak said.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak, who arrived in Bonn Monday for a two-day visit, also
met German President Roman Herzog and Chancellor Helmut Kohl this
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Kohl told Mubarak that Germany and its EU partners would do
everything possible to support the peace process in the Middle
East.
</P>
<P>
Kohl also encouraged Mubarak to continue to play "his very
important role" in the peace process, a German government
spokesman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
