<HEADLINE> Cipollini Takes Fourth Stage in Giro d'Italia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, May 20 (Xinhua) -- Mario Cipollini outsprinted the pack
Tuesday to capture his third stage victory in four days in the
Giro d'Italia.
</P>
<P>
Defending champion Pavel Tonkov retained the overall leader's
pink jersey, holding a narrow one-second lead over fellow Russian
Eugeni Berzin.
</P>
<P>
Cipollini dominated a crowded sprint following a 156-kilometer
ride from San Marino to Arezzo displaying the impressive power and
speed on the final straight which earned him the nickname of
``Super Mario.''
</P>
<P>
The 30-year-old Italian edged countryman Endrio Leoni and
Spain's Angel Edo Alsina at the finish.
</P>
<P>
Cipollini, who had won the two first stages of the Giro over
the weekend, lost the pink jersey to Tonkov on Monday following an
uphill individual time trial won by the Russian.
</P>
<P>
Tonkov is seeking to give Russia its third victory in the
Italian tour in four years.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's fourth stage, through a hilly course crossing from
the Marche to the Tuscan region, was marked by several spills in
the final kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The casualties included Colombia's Celio Rocancio, Italy's
Gabriele Colombo and Russian Vladislav Bobrik, who was bruised but
completed the stage.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's fifth stage ending in Terminillo features the first
tough mountainous stage of the 22-leg marathon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
