<HEADLINE> HK VIPs Welcome Chief Justice Recommendation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 20 (Xinhua) -- A number of Hong Kong VIPs issued
statements welcoming the recommendation of Andrew K.N. Li as the
Chief Justice of the Court of Final Appeal of the Hong Kong
Special Administration Region (HKSAR), which was announced here
today.
</P>
<P>
Anson Chan, deputy to the Governor of the HK government, said
in a statement: "I welcome the announcement that the Judicial
Officers Recommendation Commission (Designate) has recommended
that Mr. Andrew Li be appointed as the chief justice of the CFA of
the HKSAR and that Mr. Tung Chee Hwa would accept such a
recommendation and appoint Mr. Li to the position on July 1,
1997."
</P>
<P>
She described Li as "a very distinguished member of the Hong
Kong Bar" and having "an outstanding record of public service".
</P>
<P>
Justice Power, acting chief justice, said in his statement that
the announcement "is noted with great pleasure by all in the
Judiciary."
</P>
<P>
"A smooth transition of the Judiciary is of fundamental
importance for the HKSAR. All members of the Judiciary will give
unstinting support to the new chief justice when he assumes office
on July 1, 1997," Power stated.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the JORC's recommendation earlier today, HKSAR Chief
Executive Tung Chee Hwa said: "Mr. Li is an outstanding lawyer
with exceptional personal qualities who is very highly regarded in
legal and judicial circles."
</P>
<P>
"I am pleased to accept the JORC (Designate)'s recommendation
on his appointment as Chief Justice of the CFA," Tung stated.
</P>
<P>
Andrew K.N. Li was born in Hong Kong on December 12, 1948. He
holds the degrees of Master of Arts and Master of Laws from
Cambridge University.
</P>
<P>
He acted as Deputy District Court Judge in August 1982 and as
Deputy High Court Judge in June 1991. After his appointment to
the Executive Council in October 1992, it was not appropriate for
him to accept any temporary appointment with the Judiciary.
</P>
<P>
He was a member of the Executive Council and steward of the
Hong Kong Jockey Club. He served as Chairman of the University
and Polytechnic Grants Committee and the Land Development
Corporation. He served as member of the Law Reform Commission and
the Securities Commission. He is Vice-Chairman of the Council of
the HK University of Science and Technology.  
</P>
</TEXT>
