<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Supreme Leader Visits Hungary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, May 20 (Xinhua) -- Hungarian President Goncz Arpad
held talks with visiting Supreme Head of State of Malaysia Tuanku Jaafar
here today on further strengthening cooperation in science,
culture and sports.
</P>
<P>
The Hungarian President's spokesman said the two leaders also
exchanged views on other issues including situations in middle and
eastern Europe and in the former Yugoslavia, and Hungary's entry
into the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), the spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
Tuanku's visit, only a month after Hungarian Prime Minister
Gyula Horn's visit to Malaysia, is aimed at furthering
comprehensive ties between the two countries, both of which have a
common need to develop their domestic economies.
</P>
<P>
Tuanku arrived in Budapest on Monday and was scheduled to meet
Gyula Horn during his five-day stay.
</P>
<P>
Economic ties between Malaysia and Hungary have advanced
rapidly in recent years, with the bilateral trade volume amounting
to 65 million U.S. dollars in 1996. Ten joint ventures have been
established and a bank solely owned by Malaysia has been set up in
Hungary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
