<HEADLINE> Kabila Postpones Visit to Kinshasa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KINSHASA, May 20 (Xinhua) -- President of the Democratic
Republic of Congo Laurent Kabila postponed his scheduled visit to
capital Kinshasa today as local citizens and journalists waited
in vein on the main road leading to the city proper.
</P>
<P>
Many papers carried headlines such as "welcome, Kabila",
"hello, Kabila", "bring prospect to Kinshasa, Kabila" and so on
while others made wild guesses over the constitution of the new
government to be formed.
</P>
<P>
Kabila's spokesman in Kinshasa did not give exact reasons for
the delay. Earlier, local media reports said Kabila is expected
to arrive at Kinshasa from his military headquarters in the
southern city of Lubumbashi today to announce his new government.
</P>
<P>
His officers cited security reasons for the delay.
</P>
<P>
"We are making security arrangements in the presidential
palace and other key places. We are trying to improve the
security situation in the city," said one of his officer who
declined to give his name.
</P>
<P>
About 600 soldiers of the Alliance of the Democratic Forces
for the Liberation of Congo-Zaire (ADFL) chaired by Kabila,
entered mass-populated Kinshasa on may 17 meeting very little
military resistence from Mobutu's former elite presidential
guards.
</P>
<P>
However, massive looting was done overnight that day by
Mobutu's defeated and scattered soldiers as Kabila's troops, who
only narrowly managed to occupy and guard some key buildings,
facilities and military camps of Mobutu's forces, could not spare
more men to crack down on the looters.
</P>
<P>
More troops entered the city teemed with a population of five
million people to boost control and enhance security. But still,
thousands of gunmen from Mobutu's former government forces turned
underground, posing a major threat to the security situation in
the capital.
</P>
<P>
Despite the lift of curfew in the city, the streets were
deserted during the night as local citizens, espicially
foreigners, dare not go out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
