<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Calls Halt to Paratroop Restructuring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 20 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
ordered today to halt the cutting of Russian paratroop forces
because, he said, cuts to would diminish the strength of the elite
troops.
</P>
<P>
His press secretary Sergei Yastrzhembsky announced this today.
</P>
<P>
Hasty reduction and restructuring of Russia's air forces would
"objectively lead to the fall in the role and potential of the
force," Yeltsin was quoted as saying in a letter to the prime
minister, the defense minister and the chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
He called the paratroops a major strength to carry out
peace-keeping missions, and as reserve forces in peace time.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin asked Defense Minister Igor Rodionov, Prime Minister
Viktor Chernomyrdin and the chief of staff to put up a new plan.
</P>
<P>
The original reorganization timetable reduces the paratroopers
from 46,000 men to 34,000 by June 1, and leaves only three
divisions, two training centers and a special regiment.
</P>
<P>
The slashed personnel would go to the ground forces. However an
Interfax report said the Russian Defense Council was to decide at
a meeting on Thursday where precisely the troops would go.
</P>
<P>
Russian officials have been divided over the reform of the
army, which suffers from severe money shortages, poor training and
corruption.
</P>
<P>
Particularly controversial is the reduction to the paratroops'
so-called "blue berets" force which is considered one of the most
valuable branches of the Russian forces ready for service.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin's dismissal of the paratroops' chief last October was
seen as showing his determination to go ahead with the
military reform. The sacked General Yevgeny Podkolzin had been
opposed to troop cuts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970521.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukrainian Industrial Leader Lashes 1997 Draft Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Kiev, May 20 (xinhua) -- President of the Ukrainian Union of
Industries and Entrepreneurs (UUIE) Anatoly Kinakh has strongly
criticized the government's latest draft of the 1997 budget,
describing it as simplified and politically motivated.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a meeting with parliamentary deputies, he said: "The
bills of the tax reform package -- the Value Added Tax Bill, the
Company Profit Bill and Individual's Income Bill, which are
currently making their way through the parliament -- are
absolutely unable to achieve the goals set by the president to
reform the taxation system and adopt the budget to new taxation
principles,"
</P>
<P>
He said the 1997 budget should not have been drafted before the
rescheduling of ancial debts, improving the bankruptcy procedure,
balancing the national budget and overhauling the social benefit
system had been addressed.
</P>
<P>
"If these issues have not been well addressed, the budget will
not work, and domestic manufacturers will not get real support.
Neither will there be substantial progress in the effort to end
the socio-economic crisis," Kinakh said.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with the deputies, Kinakh agreed to
coordinate the UUIE's efforts with Parliament to ensure the
adoption of the 1997 budget, and the country's new taxation laws.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
