<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commonwealth Parliamentary Africa Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 20 (Xinhua) -- A three-day 28th Commonwealth
Parliamentary Association (CPA) Africa region conference started
today in Harare.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is expected to discuss the role of
parliamentarians in resolving regional conflicts, the impact of
hiv/aids on development in Africa, the role of opposition in a
multi-party democracy and enhancing women's participation in
politics.
</P>
<P>
At the opening ceremony, Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
said Africa's opposition political parties should not aim to
overthrow ruling parties as the two should instead co-exist in
order to resolve the bulk of problems afflicting the continent.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that some ruling parties had not treated the
opposition fairly.
</P>
<P>
"Some opposition parties believe that they must undo the
government in power by whatever means and that has not really
portrayed our opposition parties in good light," said Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
He said, "in some cases our own government parties have not
treated opposition groups in that manner which can cultivate
them."
</P>
<P>
"Even though we are in opposition, we belong to each other, we
are one country, we have one national anthem, we fly the same
flag and we have one nationality," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said, "although some modern democratic concepts were
greatly influenced by the developments in Europe and America,
democracy has never been the preserve of the west."
</P>
<P>
He said the continent's marginalisation was due to the
mistaken notion that mere elections could restructure supposedly
faltering political systems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
