<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Critical Development Partner: Mandela </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 20 (Xinhua) -- South African President Nelson
Mandela today said Zimbabwe is a critical development partner
with whom his country would like to increase cooperation and
trade.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a rally at the great Zimbabwe national monuments in
Masvingo province, about 300 km south of Harare, Mandela said
measures were already being taken to open up the South African
market to Zimbabwean goods by increasing free trade.
</P>
<P>
"Zimbabwe is an extremely important trade partner of South
Africa. It is our number one trade partner in Africa and number
eight in the world. Boosting trade between us is important for
creating growth, more jobs and balanced development," said
Mandela, who is on a three-day state visit to Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
He said the two countries were also increasing ties in other
areas like tourism, defence and sport.
</P>
<P>
Freedom in Southern Africa, he said, had created a chance for
the region to realise its dream of cooperation for peace,
development and prosperity through the Southern African
Development Community (SADC).
</P>
<P>
He said South Africa, which currently chairs SADC, would
ensure that regional economic integration did not only benefit
the richer and more powerful members of the group.
</P>
<P>
Mandela thanked Zimbabweans for their support in the struggle
against apartheid, saying South Africans, who gained black
majority rule in 1994, were free partly because the government
and people of Zimbabwe had considered their own freedom
incomplete while their neighbours were still oppressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
