<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Set Up Internet Node </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 20 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Development
Programme (UNDP) today donated 1.6 million U.S. dollars to
establish an internet node in Zimbabwe intended to benefit the
research community.
</P>
<P>
The two-year project, set to take off this month, will be run
by the research council of Zimbabwe in collaboration with the
Posts and Telecommunications Corporation (PTC) and the
International Telecommunications Union (ITU).
</P>
<P>
Through the internet node, Zimbabwean institutions and
individuals would have access to global information, external
databases, research, statistics and electronic mail networks.
</P>
<P>
The project activities included provision of regulatory
framework for internet services and establishment of data
communication infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
The launch of the project makes Zimbabwe the fourth southern
African country to lease a line on internet, the global
information network. 
</P>
</TEXT>
