<HEADLINE> A Brazilian Soldier of Peace-Keeping Forces in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, May 20 (Xinhua) -- A Brazilian soldier of the
peace-keeping forces of the United Nations in Angola was ambushed
and killed by a group of unidentified persons Monday in the
central province of Huambo, according to a communique of the U.N.
peace-keeping forces released here today.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian soldier, identified as Aladarque Candido dos
Santos, was ambushed and killed in the town of Vila Nova in the
province while escorting a civilian vehicle convoy.
</P>
<P>
Another Brazilian soldier, Samuel Sobrinho Correa, was
seriously wounded during the ambush and sent to a hospital for
treatment. His conditions are now stable.
</P>
<P>
So far, 32 soldiers of the peace-keeping forces in Angola
have lost their lives since the forces entered the country in
early 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970521.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FAO Predicts Food Shortage in Great Lakes, East </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 20 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Food and
Agriculture Organization (FAO) has predicted serious food supply
problems in the Great Lakes and East African regions due to a
prolonged drought and civil strife.
</P>
<P>
In its latest report of "Food Supply and Crop Prospects in
Sub-Saharan Africa", FAO said that the food situation facing
Rwandan refugees in Eastern Zaire was grave with hundreds dying
of starvation and disease.
</P>
<P>
In Burundi, the report issued here today noted, the food
supply situation remained tight following a poor 1997 first
season harvest due to the intensified civil strife in late 1996.
</P>
<P>
In Rwanda, the 1997 first season food production remained
below the pre-civil strife average with about 2.6 million people,
or one third of its population, are in need of food assistance.
</P>
<P>
The report prepared by FAO's Global Information and Early
Warnings System said that severe drought and floods in Eastern
Africa in recent months had led to serious food supply problems.
</P>
<P>
More than three million people are threatened with the food
shortage in large parts of Kenya, Tanzania, Somalia, Ethiopia,
Eritrea, Sudan and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
In Kenya, the food supply situation is critical in the
northeastern and Eastern provinces and parts of Central and Coast
provinces affected by drought during the 1996/97 "short rains"
season.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government has declared the drought a national
disaster and appealed to the international community for
emergency assistance until the next harvest in July.
</P>
<P>
The report stated that large parts of northern Tanzania,
eastern and southeastern Ethiopia, southern Somalia and eastern
Uganda were also seriously affected by the drought.
</P>
<P>
However, the report noted, a good harvest is in prospect in
southern Africa, particularly in Malawi, Mozambique, Zambia and
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the good cereal harvest in 1996, the southern
Africa's overall food supply situation at the end of the 1996/97
has considerably improved compared to the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The report pointed out that even though the aggregate food aid
needs of Sub-Saharan Africa in 1997 were expected to be about 20
percent lower than 1996, they remained high, estimated at about
1.9 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The decline, it added, was attributed to good harvest in
western Africa and parts of the Horn of Africa in 1996, as well
as the favourable harvest outlook for southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
The report called for the international community to focus its
attention on extreme suffering of Rwandan refugees in eastern
Zaire and the precarious food supply situation in East Africa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970521.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, Ethiopia Sign Cultural Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, May 20 (Xinhua) -- China and Ethiopia today
signed here the implementation program for the cultural agreement
between the two governments from 1997 to 2000.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice-minister of Culture Li Yuanchao and Ethiopian
Vice-Minister of Information and Culture Bisrat Gashawtena signed
the program on behalf of their respective governments.
</P>
<P>
According to the program, the two sides will exchange
delegations and performing troupes, hold exhibitions and
strengthen cooperation in the domain of culture, education,
sports and mass-media.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the signing ceremony, the chinese vice-minister
said his delegation was here to push forward the cooperation
relations between the two countries in the cultural field.
</P>
<P>
The signing of implementation program indicated the new
beginning of cooperation relations between the two countries in
the cultural field, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian vice-minister said the relations between the two
countries reached its highest stage with the historic visit to
Ethiopia by Chinese President Jiang Zemin, adding that his visit
had a wider implication for the all-rounded relations of the two
peoples and countries in the future.
</P>
<P>
Li today held talks with Ethiopian Minister Woldemichael Chamo
and vice-minister Bisrat separately here.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government cultural delegation led by Li arrived
here today for a 4-day visit to Ethiopia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
