<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N.to Deploy 200 More Observers to Liberia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 20 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations is to deploy 200
additional short-term observers to Liberia for the country's
legislative and presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
They will join the 36 U.N. civilians and military observers already
in Liberia, Tuliameni Klomoh, special representative of the UN
Secretary-General, said today in Abuja, capital of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the observers now in Liberia conduct daily
reconnaissance missions to the 13 counties of the country to gather
information on road conditions and population distribution patterns.
</P>
<P>
They also report on the activities of political parties in the
interior part of the country and the movement of refugees in the
border areas, Klomoh said.
</P>
<P>
They would be instrumental to verifying voters' registration which
is a crucial aspect of the electoral process, he added.
</P>
<P>
On voter education, he said, a professional radio programer
employed by the UN observers mission is developing a coherent program
that would ensure voters receive neutral and factual information on
the electoral process.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the UN development program has been providing Liberia's
seven-member indepenent electoral commission with logistic assistance,
while the UN High Commissioner for Refugees has started a voluntary
repartriation program for the Liberians who fled the country during
the seven-year civil war.
</P>
<P>
The polls in Liberia was earlier scheduled for May 30 but has been
shift to July at the request of some political parties who insist that
a postponement will give enough room for better preparation.
</P>
<P>
West African leaders are to meet tomorrow in Abjua to decide a new
date for the elections.
</P>
<P>
On the new election date, Kalomoh advised against a prolonged delay
in the elections, saying "ECOWAS has invested so much in Liberia and
it would be disastrous if all the noble sacrifices made were
compromised merely because of lack of extension of the election date
by a few more days."  
</P>
</TEXT>
