<HEADLINE> Deutsche Bank 1st-Quarter Profits Up 21 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 20 (Xinhua) -- Germany's biggest commercial bank
Deutsche Bank today reported a 21 percent surge in its
first-quarter profits and was hopeful of more full-year earnings
than in 1996.
</P>
<P>
It said that thanks to a strong stock market, the bank's
operating profits after risk provisions hit 1.4 billion marks (826
million U.S. dollars) in the first quarter of this year, while
pre-tax profits reached 1.3 billion marks (767 million dollars),
up 28 percent.
</P>
<P>
At the annual shareholders' meeting, the bank's new chairman
Rolf Breuer outlined plans to reorient the bank's operation
strategies, including phase-out of the bank's large industrial
holdings in Germany to build up stakes in foreign companies,
focusing of business in such areas as investment banking as well
as possible quitting of other operations including consumer
finance.
</P>
<P>
Breuer succeeds Hilmar Kopper, who presided as chairman today
of his last annual shareholders' meeting. 
</P>
