<HEADLINE> Germany Still Leads World's Trade Fair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 20 (Xinhua) -- Despite increasing overseas
competitions, in particular from Asia, Germany still leads the
world in organizing trade fairs, with six of the world's top-ten
fair organizers with the largest turnovers now headquartered in
the country, a German newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to the annual report issued by the Exhibition and
Fair Committee of German Economy (AUMA), Germany in 1996 attracted
144,000 exhibitors, nearly 45 percent from foreign countries, to
show their products on a total exhibition floorspace of more than
six million square meters. Fair visitors totaled 8.97 million, 18
percent of them were from foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
The AUMA expected about 10 million visitors for the 131 major
trade fairs planned for 1997 in the country with 150,000
exhibitors on a total exhibition area of 6.3 million square
meters, the German daily Sueddeutsche Zeitung reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The German trade fair organizing companies as a whole achieved
a turnover of 3.5 billion German marks (2.1 billion U.S. dollars)
and employed about 6,000 people in 1996.
</P>
<P>
AUMA general director Hermann Kresse said the German trade fair
industry is a growth sector and will remain one also in the
future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
