<HEADLINE> EU Calls for Improvement of Bathing Water Quality </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, May 20 (Xinhua) -- Still one out of three fresh water
bathing zones in the European Union (EU) countries is
insufficiently monitored or does not meet the minimum quality
requirements, says a report published here today.
</P>
<P>
The report, on quality of bathing water in EU member countries,
covers about 13,000 seaside beaches and 6,000 fresh water areas.
</P>
<P>
Mrs. Ritt Bjerregaard, EU commissioner for environment,
therefore urged everyone and every country concerned to make every
effort in improving the quality of fresh water zones, while
continuing the efforts already made and preserving the good
quality at seaside.
</P>
<P>
She called particularly on Germany, France, the Netherlands,
Spain and Portugal "to prove over the next bathing season that
they are able to improve the situation."
</P>
<P>
"They have shown that they are able to do it for their seaside
beaches, so I am confident that they can do it for their fresh
water bathing areas as well," she said.
</P>
<P>
The commissioner explained that it was not only the health
aspect that attracted people to go to the beach, but the
"aesthetic" aspect of the water should also be taken into account.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, the European Commission, the EU's executive body,
adopted a proposal for a revised directive on bathing water
quality, which was aimed at further improving the water quality in
bathing zones of EU member countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
