<HEADLINE> 6,800 UNITA Soliders Disbanded in Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, May 20 (Xinhua) -- More than 6,800 UNITA soldiers have
been disbanded in the first phase of the implementation of the
rapid disbandment plan in Angola so far, a UN source said here
today.
</P>
<P>
Rosa Malingo, an official from the UN Humanitarian Aid
Coordination Agency, told reporters that the disbandment work is
still under way in several quartering camps scattering in Huambo
Province in central Angola and there are also 5,000 UNITA
soldiers waiting for their disbandment.
</P>
<P>
The second phase of the implementation of the rapid
disbandment plan will be started on June 2. In this stage, 10,000
UNITA soldiers will be disbanded, she added.
</P>
<P>
The UN official also noted that the number of deserters who
have left the camps without authorization among the UNITA
soldiers is still increasing, which is adding more difficulties
to the selection of soldiers into the unified army of Angola.
</P>
<P>
She revealed that the number of the deserters has reached more
than 25,500 so far, adding that all the 15 assembling camps are
make efforts to persuade the deserters to return to their
camps. 
