<HEADLINE> Germany Demands Swift Improvement in European </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 20 (Xinhua) -- German Research Minister Juergen
Ruettgers today urged the European Commission to make it a top
priority to upgrade the transmission speed of the European
research computer network so as to remove "artificial national
boundaries" within Europe in computer networking.
</P>
<P>
Ruettgers made the remarks on the occasion of the enlargement
of the European research network through the TEN-34
(Trans-European Network), which went into operation Tuesday in
Cambridge, Britain.
</P>
<P>
TEN-34 links the national research networks in Europe and
improves European researchers' access to data-banks in other
countries. However, it has only a data transmission speed of 34
megabit per second, a far cry from the current German research
network with 155 megabit per second.
</P>
<P>
European research cooperation needs efficient transmission
possibilities across national borders, Ruettgers said. If the
European network cannot keep pace with national ones, European
computer world will have to deal with artificial national
boundaries which have just been removed by road traffic, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
