<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's PM Courts EU Investors For MSC Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 20 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir
Mohamad outlined here today his plans to create the world's first
digital state that will enable companies to explore the limits of
multimedia.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at Imperial Collete, the Prime Minister focused on the
MSC and the opportunities it will create for Western investment
and expertise.
</P>
<P>
The Multimedia Super Corridor (MSC) is a 15 by 50 kilometer
zone extending south from Malaysia's capital Kuala Lumpur, to the
new Kuala Lumpur International Airport.
</P>
<P>
The MSC will offer a unique environment, combining
world-leading IT and physical infrastructure with a comprehensive
package of incentives and support, in which multimedia companies
can develop new technologies and applications.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's future capital city of Putrajaya and the new city of
Cyberjaya, the world's first IT city designed from ground up, will
form the nucleus of this Multimedia Super Corridor, according to
Mahathir.
</P>
<P>
The MSC will have seven "Flagship Applications", each designed
to pioneer the strategy behind specific aspects of the electronic
economy.
</P>
<P>
Standards and solutions for each area are already being
developed by the Malaysian government working in partnership with
Microsoft, Sun, Netscape, EDS and IBM, the Prime Minister said.
</P>
<P>
To ensure timely implementation and smooth the way for
companies interested in using the MSC for their operations, the
Malaysian Government has set up the Multimedia Development
Corporation that functions as a high-powered one-stop shop for the
MSC.
</P>
<P>
More than 800 potential investors from EU countries attended
the open conference on the Multimedia Super Corridor.  
</P>
</TEXT>
