<HEADLINE> German Minister Concerned About Companies' Neglect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Concerned about dwindling
opportunities for young people to get vacational trainings, German
Youth Minister Claudia Nolte has proposed to punish those
companies which do not offer vacational trainings.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the German newspaper Express, Nolte said
those companies which do not train young people should not be
allowed to get government research promotion funds and should be
denied of government contracts, said reports today.
</P>
<P>
If appeals cannot make enough impact, such measures should be
considered, Nolte said, adding that it is unacceptable for a
number of large enterprises to duck their social responsibility
for training.
</P>
<P>
Plagued by a sluggish economy and record-high unemployment in
the country, German companies are increasingly reluctant to
conduct vacational training. According to a survey published
earlier this month, lack of apprenticeship is among the top
concerns shared by German youngsters from 12 to 24 years old.
</P>
</TEXT>
