<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Gears up Relief Work in Cyclone-hit Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The relief activities were going on
in full swing in the cyclone-hit areas under the direct
supervision of Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina today, said a high
official of the Bangladeshi government.
</P>
<P>
Jawadul Karim, press secretary to the prime minister, told
newsmen that the prime minister today rushed to the affected areas
in Hatiya, Swandip, Teknaf and Banskhali to see for herself the
sufferings of the people in those counties.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Monday, a devastating cyclonic storm struck the
coastal belt of Bangladesh at a frightful speed ranging from 180
to 200 kilometers per hour, tearing and twisting everything that
came in its way.
</P>
<P>
Jawadul Karim denied a report in some local newspapers that
about 500 people were feared killed by the storm, saying only 95
so far were killed, two persons missing and 7,844 injured.
</P>
<P>
He said the relief and rehabilitation coordination center in
the Prime Minister's Secretariat has been maintaining the constant
contact with the control rooms in the district headquarters as
well as those in different ministries to monitor the post cyclone
activities.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,899 cattle were lost during the cyclone, he said, adding
that crops on 29,951 hectares of land were damaged.
</P>
<P>
The storm also damaged 75 bridges, 153 kilometers of roads and
embankment, 608 educational institutions and 718 cyclone shelters,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The press secretary said 2.55 million Taka (about 63,750 U.S.
dollars) in cash has been allocated from the Prime Minister's
Relief Fund for distribution among the cyclone-hit people.
</P>
<P>
Besides, about 34,000 pieces of clothes, 39,000 pieces of old
clothes, 50,600 pieces of plates and glasses, 400 tons of wheat,
2,100 tins of biscuits have been allocated for distribution in the
cyclone-hit areas, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
