<HEADLINE> Russian PM Urges Big Budget Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Russian new government
urged the parliament Wednesday to back a plan demanding drastic
spending cuts to bring the budget into line with the poor revenue.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin made the call in his
accounts for the first four months.
</P>
<P>
The government, reshuffled and rejuvenated by President Boris
Yeltsin two months ago, is expected to present a bill calling for
spending cuts of 108 trillion roubles (19 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said Russia gathered only 64.4 percent of
the tax revenue budgeted for the first four months of the year.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin said the GDP (gross domestic product) was keeping
the same level as the same period last year. Industrial production
was improving despite the six percent inflation in the first
four months of this year.
</P>
<P>
There were rises in automobile production, textiles and other
industry products.
</P>
<P>
He also said real income had gone up by four percent, and
unemployment had leveled off.  
</P>
</TEXT>
