<HEADLINE> Nepali Youth Climber Scales Mount Qomolangma </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, May 21 (Xinhua) -- A Nepali climber today reached
the summit of Mount Qomolangma through the southern route, Nepal's
Tourism Ministry announced here.
</P>
<P>
Danuree Sherpa, 36, who reached the 8,848-meter peak at 1:00 PM
(local time) today, belongs to a six-member Nepali Youth
Expedition which left here nearly one month ago for the expedition.
</P>
<P>
The team had been stranded in a camp at a height of nearly
6,000 meters for over 10 days despite its earlier plan to make
their final attempt in mid-May.
</P>
<P>
The youth expedition was sponsored and organized by a Nepali
youth organization to show Nepali youth's commitment to world
peace and herald the 14th World Youth and Student Festival, which
is to be held in Havana, Cuba in July this year, organizers said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, four members of an international Qomolangma
expedition led by British climber Jonathan Tinker and two Nepali
mountain guides also successfully scaled Qomolangma via the south
face, the ministry said, adding that so far the names and others
details of the summitters are not available.
</P>
<P>
Five members of a Russian expedition also reached today the
8,463-meter-high Mount Makalu today via west face in northern
Nepal, according to the ministry.
</P>
<P>
The five are Igor Bougatchevski, Dimitri Pavlenko, Alexei
Bolotov, Iouro Ermatchek and Nikolai Jiline, it added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
