<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgarian Parliament Elects New Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria's parliament today approved
as prime minister Ivan Kostov, the leader of the Union of
Democratic Forces (UDF).
</P>
<P>
Kostov won the nomination with 179 votes to 54, with no
abstentions.
</P>
<P>
Kostov, 48, was finance minister in the Dimiter Popov
government in 1991 and the Filip Dimitrov cabinet in 1992.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, Kostov, a former professor of economics, became head
of the UDF, which defeated the ruling Socialists and won the
legislative elections last April 19.
</P>
<P>
Later today, Kostov introduced new cabinet ministers and the
guidelines of his government policies to the parliament.
</P>
<P>
Economic reforms and luring more foreign investment would be
the government's most urgent tasks, Kostov said.
</P>
<P>
He also pledged to privatize all industrial and commercial
enterprises, including most infrustructure projects, by 1998.
</P>
<P>
Kostov said the new government would also focus on cracking
down on crime and corruption and seeking entry to the European
Union and the North Atlantic Treaty Organization.
</P>
<P>
The UDF reached consensus on these guidelines with Bulgaria's
major political parties after its victory in the April 19
legislative elections, and the Bulgarian parliament also made a
national reconciliation announcement.
</P>
<P>
This laid a solid foundation for Kostov and his party, which
are expected to receive broad support from political parties and
common people.
</P>
<P>
Kostov named three deputy prime ministers, who will be in
charge of the economy, regional development and public affairs,
and ideology and institutional reforms respectively.
</P>
<P>
The new government inherited three ministers from the caretaker
cabinet among its 14 ministries.
</P>
<P>
The Bulgarian parliament is now debating the government's
policy guidelines, after which it will vote on the new cabinet.
</P>
</TEXT>
