<HEADLINE> Namibia Relaxes Foreign Exchange Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Namibia announced
today that it will relax foreign exchange control measures.
</P>
<P>
In its statement issued in Windhoek, the bank said it had
decided to abolish indicative limits on current account
transactions "except where limits are retained to make the
remaining restriction on capital outflow effective."
</P>
<P>
Namibians travelling abroad would be allowed a maximum of
80,000 Namibian dollars (18,000 U.S. dollars) and 25,000 ND (5682
dollars) per child under 12 each calendar year. This increased
from ND60,000 (13,636 dollars) allowed previously.
</P>
<P>
"The previous distinction between neighbouring and other
countries has been dispensed with," the bank said.
</P>
<P>
Regarding capital account transactions, the limits for direct
foreign investment have been increased from ND20 million (4.5
million dollars) to ND30 million (6.8 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
"Namibian corporates will now be allowed to raise financing
abroad on the strength of their local balance sheet, while, in
the past, offshore financing had to be obtained without any
recourse to or guarantee from Namibia," the bank said. enditem

=05211351

=05211356
NNNN
22:00 22:00 g # PAB
</P>
