<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECA Executive Secretary on Strengthening Africa's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, May 21 (Xinhua) -- K.Y. Amoako, executive
secretary of the United Nations Economic Commission for Africa
(ECA), today said ECA attaches much importance to the
strengthening of Africa's information capacities.
</P>
<P>
In his opening statement at the seventh meeting of the
Coordina- ting Committee on African Statistical Development
(CASD) at Africa Hall here, Amoako described the information
development in Africa as "very unsatisfactory", saying that "the
state of information development in Africa is characterized by
lack of or poor quality of data, weak or inadequate
telecommunication systems, lack of a critical mass of trained
personnel, and laws and regulations that impede information
flows."
</P>
<P>
The ECA chief said the rehabilitation of Africa's statistical
infrastructure has continued to be a priority area for ECA in
order to assist in the development of sustainable national
statistical systems.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that all African countries, and in particular their
national statistical offices, will be linked to ECA and other
international organizations, to enable speedier transfer of
development information.
</P>
<P>
The two-day meeting will listen to report to the CASD by the
secretariat, consider proposed task forces and discuss
"mobilization of resources for the implementation of CASD
activities".
</P>
<P>
CASD was established in 1992 in response to the recognition of
the need to ensure the success of technical cooperation at both
national and regional levels through proper coordination of
various statistical development activities in Africa. According
to the mandate of the CASD, it acts as coordinating body for
statistical development activities in Africa and monitors overall
implementation of the Addis Ababa Plan of action for statistical
development in Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
