<HEADLINE> Manila Confident of Continued Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Despite the recent slowdown in the
stock market, the Philippine government remained optimistic that
the economy will continue to grow and the 7-8 percent growth
target for this year will be attained.
</P>
<P>
Socio-Economic Planning Secretary Cielito Habito said here
today that early economic indicators all point to a continued
robust overall growth in the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
The month-on-month manufacturing growth presents "an
encouraging picture", with the output growing by an average of
over 7 percent in January and February this year, he said.
</P>
<P>
Agricultural growth was also very "encouraging" by registering
a 22 percent growth during the first quarter in stark contrast to
the 3.4 percent in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Habito also disclosed that sales earnings of major companies
have expanded, while the country's inflation rate and the growth
in the merchandise trade deficit continued to slow down.
</P>
<P>
"We, therefore, see the full-year Gross National Product growth
target of 7-8 percent to be attainable at this point," Habito
said, adding that the economy would improve further in the latter
quarters this year.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Stock Exchange suffered several sharp plunges
this month amid fears that the country's economy had become
"overheated" as in Thailand.  
</P>
</TEXT>
