<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Arafat Holds US Responsible for Peace Process Impasse (I) (by Huai Chengbo) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 21 (Xinhua) -- President of the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) Yasser Arafat hit the nail on the head
when he pointed out Monday that the deadlocked Israeli-Palestinian
peace process is exacerbated by a lack of U.S. pressure on Israel.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian journalists told Xinhua that although Arafat was
reluctant to openly point an accusing finger at the U.S., yet
what he said holds water.
</P>
<P>
No one in the U.S., including President Bill Clinton,
prevented Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu from scoring
what he considered to be a major achievement on issues related to
the final status of Jerusalem and Jewish settlements in the
occupied Palestinian territories. He successfully defied both
U.S. advice and the harsh Arab and international opposition to
construction of a new settlement at Har Homa in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
U.S. efforts to reverse the deterioration, sparked by the
beginning of construction at Har Homa and the subsequent Hamas
suicde bombing attack in Tel Aviv that killed three Israeli
women, have followed prescriptions established by the hardline
Netanyahu government.
</P>
<P>
These prescriptions do not include reconsideration of the scope
of "further redeployment" or of the decision on the Jewish
settlement construction on Har Homa. On the contrary, they urge
Palestinian efforts, in secretary of State Madeleine Albright's
approving words, to "dismantle the infrastructure of the
(Palestinian) terrorist organizations."
</P>
<P>
During his visit to the United States in early April,
Netanyahu did not accept any U.S. proposals for Israeli
confidence-building measures.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu also declared that Israel does not intend to
procceed with the second "further redeployment," scheduled to
take place in September, if his proposal for accelerated final status
negotiations is accepted and, contrary to U.S. expectations, this
second redeployment will be no larger than the first -- that is,
the transfer to Palestinian control of a further 2 percent of the
West Bank.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970521.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Arafat Holds US Responsible for Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ha'aretz, a leading Hebrew daily in Israel, reported on April
9 that "Clinton did not specifically request that Netanyahu stop
construction at Har Homa, or in settlements in general, but
asked that Israel refrain from taking unilateral decisions as
long as negotiations continue and that it notify the U.S. in
advance about all construction in the occupied territories."
</P>
<P>
Secretary of State Albright took a more forceful line at
her meeting with Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai in
Washington. The meeting was described by an Israeli official as
"uncomfortable."
</P>
<P>
Albright reportedly explained that the settlement expansion
imperils chances for dialogue, asked for an explanation of
Mordechai's recent approval of new construction in various
settlements, and demanded a freeze on all settlement
construction.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian officials were subsequently informed by U.S. Middle
 East peace coordinator Dennis Ross that the United States cannot
halt settlement construction at Har Homa to meet one of the
Palestinians' central demands. The idea of a settlement freeze
has been incorporated in a more general U.S. effort to persuade
Netanyahu to refrain from taking unspecified unilateral measures.
</P>
<P>
U.S. efforts to reverse the Har Homa decision or to win
an Israeli pledge to freeze settlements have not been pursued
with vigor or with any apparent confidence of their success.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration, by its long-standing support for
the settlements' "natural growth," recognized this element of the
process. The U.S. refusal to view settlement expansion as a
unilateral action that prejudices negotiations of a final status
issues was based on the same reasoning.
</P>
<P>
The problems that have dominated the headlines, however, have
not affected the strategic interests binding U.S.-Israeli
cooperation. As the Israeli newspaper Globes pointed out, "Even
as Albright was making her demands, Mordechai was being assured
by American officials that the present high level of
U.S.-Israeli defense cooperation would continue unabated, with or
without regard to the unfolding developments at Har Homa or in
the West Bank.:
</P>
<P>
Indeed, according to reports from Washington, American
support for the Israeli-developed Arrow anti-missile system will
now be substantially increased, other defense aid will not be cut
back, and current levels of intelligence sharing between the two
countries will remain very much intact. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970521.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Punish Violent Crimes Severely </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The South African government
will inflict heavier punishment on violent crimes, Justice
Minister Dullah Omar said today.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet has decided that murderers, rapists, robbers,
hijackers and drug traffickers would be put in jail for at least
15 years, and a legislation to this effect would be tabled in
parliament soon, Omar said.
</P>
<P>
Under the bill, first offenders would receive a minimum
sentence of 15 years, second would be sent away for at least 20
years, and third and subsequent offenders would be sent to jail
for a minimum of 25 years.
</P>
<P>
Omar said the courts would also be empowered to impose minimum
sentences for crims relating to corruption, fraud, forgery, and
theft involving amounts in excess of 500,000 Rands (114,000 U.S.
dollars) and where it was proved that such an offence was
commttted by a syndicate.
</P>
<P>
For these crimes, a minimum sentence of 10 years would be
imposed on first offenders, 15 years for second and 20 years for
those guilty of third and subsequent offences. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
