<HEADLINE> PKK Kidnaps 5 Workers in Southeastern Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Rebels of the illegal Kurdish
Workers' Party (PKK) today kidnaped five workers when they
attacked a coal mine near Sirnak province of southeastern
Turkey, the semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
A group of PKK militants threatened the workers out of
the mine with weapons at noon and gathered them, said the
agency, adding that the PKK guerrillas later took them straight
to the Cudi mountain.
</P>
<P>
The PKK rebels launched various attacks in southeastern
Turkey as a Turkish contingent of about 25,000 to 50,000
troops has crossed the border into northern Iraq, trying to
eradicate all the PKK militants based there.
</P>
<P>
The PKK rebels blocked Sunday night for several hours the
southeastern Mardin-Sirnak main road by burning two oil tanker
trucks, said the agency.
</P>
<P>
In a separate incident, the PKK militants launched a dozen
of rocket attacks against the government buildings on the town
of Derik in nearby Mardin province without causing casualties.
</P>
<P>
In another development, the PKK rebels also ambushed village
guards in Kahramanmaras in southeastern Turkey Monday evening,
killing one and wounding four others.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish security forces are continuing the cross-border
military operation in northern Iraq, which started on May 14
and so far, at least 1,300 PKK rebels have been killed in
the operation.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Turkish Foreign Ministry spokesman Omer Akbel told
reporters here today that Syria should bear important
responsibility over supporting the PKK, which has been fighting a
nearly 13-year-old separatist war, claiming more that 23,000
lives, including PKK rebels, civilians and government troops in
eastern and southeastern Turkey since August 1984. 
</P>
</TEXT>
