<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stock Speculation by State Enterprises, Listed Companies Banned (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 21 (Xinhua) -- China's central economic and
financial authorities has issued a regulation to ban state-owned
enterprises and listed companies from stock speculation.
</P>
<P>
Jointly issued by the State Council's Securities Committee, the
People's Bank of China, and the State Economic and Trade
Commission recently, the regulation noted that over-speculation
and activities against state rules are rampant in the country's
fledgling securities market.
</P>
<P>
Recently, the regulation said, capital from the state-owned
commercial banks has been flowing into the stock market
continuously and through various channels.
</P>
<P>
To speculate in stocks, some state-owned enterprises put bank
loans or their own development fund on the stock market, while a
number of listed companies invested with bank loans or money
raised from the issue of shares.
</P>
<P>
"This kind of phenomenon has both stimulated speculation in the
stock market and put the state assets at high risk," said the
regulation.
</P>
<P>
In order to bring into play the function of the socialist stock
market and maintain a normal market order, the regulation noted,
the speculation on the stock market by state-owned enterprises and
listed companies should be halted.
</P>
<P>
It required that the state-owned enterprises should not be
involved in stock speculation or provide funds for other
institutions to speculate in stocks, nor should they use money
loaned from state banks to purchase stocks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970521.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two More U.S. Athletes Test Positive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Two more U.S. athletes failed in
doping tests, according to the sources of the International
Amateur Athletic Federation (IAAF) on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The scandal came just days after the emergence of cases
involving leading American track stars Sandra Farmer-Patrick and
Mary Slaney.
</P>
<P>
Athletics sources said that the U.S. Track and Field
Association was expected to report the new cases to IAAF in the
next few days.
</P>
<P>
Source close to the cases revealled that there are two new
positive tests. They are not big-name athletes but definitely from
the United States.
</P>
<P>
The banned substances involved in the cases or when the
athletes were caught were still uncertain. But the emergence of
the positive tests is a further blow to American athletics.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Track and Field authorities were criticised by the IAAF on
Tuesday for their procedures over the cases of Farmer-Patrick and
Slaney who tested positive several months before last year's
Atlanta Olympics in August.
</P>
<P>
Farmer-Patrick was allowed to take part in the Olympics and has
only been banned for four years for steroid abuse.
</P>
<P>
The Slaney case has yet to be concluded almost a year after she
was found to have high levels of the banned substance testosterone
in the body during a test at the U.S. trials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
