<HEADLINE> Stock Speculation by State Enterprises, Listed Companies Banned (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It also banned all listed companies from using bank loans or
money raised from the issue of shares to buy stocks, or financing
other institutions to engage in stock speculation.
</P>
<P>
"Any state-owned enterprises or listed companies that hold
listed stocks for the purpose of long-term investment should
report to the securities exchanges, and each of them is allowed to
open only one A shares account at the exchange in the name of the
legal person," it added.
</P>
<P>
It demanded that governments at all levels, stock exchanges,
and securities management institutions across the country make a
full check of local state-owned enterprises, listed companies, and
existing stock accounts, and report the results to the central
securities supervisory bodies.
</P>
<P>
It went on to say that any state-owned enterprises and listed
companies that continue with stock speculation after the issue of
the regulation, if found out, would be fined, and their illicit
incomes confiscated.
</P>
<P>
"Enterprises that used bank loans for the purchase of stocks
shall get no more loans, and must return the misused money within
a limited period of time," it added.
</P>
<P>
It also stipulated that principal and direct responsible people
of the state-owned enterprises that violate the regulation should
be dismissed by their competent departments, while managers of the
listed companies breaking the rules would be denied market access
by the China Securities Regulatory Commission. 
</P>
