<HEADLINE> India Fixes This Year's Export Growth Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 21 (XINHUA) -- The Indian government has fixed
this year's export growth target at 20 percent to achieve 40
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The higher export growth was needed to achieve the target of
100 billion U.S. dollars by the end of the Ninth Five-Year Plan
(1997/98-2001/02), Union Commerce Secretary P.P. Prabhu said here
Tuesday at a meeting of the heads of export promotion councils and
commodity boards.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was held to evolve a medium-term export strategy,
Commercial Ministry sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
Exports in the country had grown 4.1 percent to 33.10 billion
dollars in 1996-97.
</P>
<P>
Minister of State for Commerce Bolla Buli Ramaiah, who attended
the meeting, said that in order to promote exports of the
small-scale sector, a core group would be set up under the
chairmanship of the director general of foreign trade. The
guidelines for recognition of the status of export houses/trading
houses had been relaxed.
</P>
<P>
He assured the textile exporters of facilitating the imports of
raw materials as well as embellishments in order to promote
value-added exports.  
</P>
</TEXT>
