<HEADLINE> Heavy Fighting Rages Afghan Northern Provinces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Afghan Islamic militia Taliban
and forces loyal to northern warlord Rashid Dostum today were
engaged in fierce fighting around Sheberghan, capital of northern
Jowzjan province, Pakistan Television reported.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban, who have launched a two-pronged offensive against
Dostum-controlled areas, are now advancing towards Mazar-e-Sharif,
Dostum's headquarters, about 300 kilometers northwest of Kabul,
PTV said.
</P>
<P>
Sources said that Dostum's forces are presently strengthening
their defense positions in Mazar-e-Sharif.
</P>
<P>
Following the revolt by Dostum's right-hand man, general Abdul
Malik, the defense line of the Dostum's forces has collapsed, PTV
said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, the anti-Taliban alliance, which is
composed mainly of forces of Dostum and Ahmad Masood, former
military chief of the ousted Afghan government, held crisis talks
after Malik's defection.
</P>
<P>
The advance of the Taliban can only be stemmed if the emergency
negotiations persuade Malik to rejoin the forces of Dostum, a
spokesman of the anti-Taliban alliance was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"High level negotiations are still going on with Abdul Malik,
and this is a very sensitive and critical situation for us," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"The defection of Malik and the loss of so much ground is a
very big setback, but there is a chance he can be convinced to
change his mind," he said.
</P>
<P>
Malik, who was a senior commander in Dostum's forces, Monday
switched allegiance to the Taliban, taking with him two provinces
and allowing the Taliban to march into another he had cut off.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban, taking advantage of the revolt in the alliance
ranks, launched a major offensive Tuesday making crucial gains in
central and northern Afghanistan, although issuing conflicting
reports on the extent of its gains.  
</P>
</TEXT>
