<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat, Mubarak Meet on Peace Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) President Yasser Arafat today met with Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak as the deadlocked peace process shows no trace of a
breakthrough, the Egyptian MENA news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, who arrived here at noon on a lightning visit, had a
tete-a-tete with Mubarak before it went into an expanded session
involving Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa, PLO Executive
Committee chief Mahmoud Abbas, Palestinian Minister of Planning
and International Cooperation Nabil Shaath and other senior aides.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders are expected to review outcome of their recent
contacts to salvage the faltering peace process which came to a
standstill after Israel started the construction of a new
settlement in East Jerusalem in March.
</P>
<P>
Also on the agenda will be Arafat's recent meeting with EU
Mideast peace envoy Miguel Moratinos who made a shuttle diplomacy
in the Mideast, following U.S. Mideast trouble-shooter Dennis
Ross's futile mediation for a breakthrough in the peace march.
</P>
<P>
Israel held secret crisis talks overnight Tuesday with the
Palestinians, which failed to ease a two-month-old deadlock
because Israel refused to discuss freezing Jewish settlements on
occupied lands, according to a PNA spokesman.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with a German newspaper Tuesday, Mubarak said
that a six-month suspension of Jewish settlement building in Arab
Jerusalem could restart the stricken peace process.
</P>
<P>
The president said if Israel observed the Oslo accord, a broad
interim agreement that promised security for Israel and self-rule
for Palestinians, the Palestinians would be ready to find a
compromise formula to settle Jerusalem status.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has been deeply involved in the Mideast peace process
since it made peace with Israel in 1979.
</P>
<P>
Israel refuses to budge on its settlement building in Jerusalem
which it wants to have as future capital while the Palestinians
insist on stopping the project before resuming the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
After U.S. Mideast coordinator Dennis Ross left the region
empty-handed last weekend, Arafat blamed the lack of American
pressure on Israel for a breakdown of the "core bargain" of the
1993 Israeli-PLO Oslo deal.
</P>
<P>
Disappointed with Ross' performance during the nine-day
mission, he has asked U.S. President Bill Clinton to personally
get involved in efforts to break the impasse.
</P>
<P>
However, prospects for a breakthrough remain daunting, as
Israel regards the EU firmly siding with the Palestinians, while
Palestinians see the U.S. tilting toward Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970521.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 12:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Supreme Leader Pledges No Vote Rigging in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Supreme Leader Ali
Khamenei today pledged no vote rigging in the presidential
elections slated for May 23.
</P>
<P>
Khamenei said that two bodies, the Interior Ministry and the
Guardians Council as well as he himself, will watch against any
fraud in the elections.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian leader made the remarks on the eve of the
presidential elections in a bid to dispel the wide and strong
suspicion held by his citizens over the fairness of the election,
the vote-reading in particular.
</P>
<P>
A great number of eligible voters, including university
students, professors, bookshop keepers and taxi drivers, are
gossiping their worries over the possible vote rigging on the
coming Friday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing high-ranking officials and families of prisoners of
war and the missing in action during the 1980-1988 war with
Iraq, he assured the people of the whole country by saying, "I
myself will be watchful and will not let any one to commit any
fraud in the elections."
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the statement by President Akbar Hashemi
Rafsanjani last Friday, Khamenei said that the president's
"compassionate" statements have been misinterpreted by foreign
media which misled some analysts and friends of Iran to think
that the Friday elections will be rigged.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian leader also called on the people to actively take
part in the elections and defeat the plot by what he called
foreign enemies of Iran.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, Rafsanjani openly warned Interior Ministry
officials against any kinds of cheating at ballot boxes and
called on election observers to maintain strict impartiality.
</P>
<P>
"Any effort to rig the elections should be seen as a grave sin
and inexcusable treason," he addressed a large crowd of people on
the Tehran University campus.
</P>
<P>
The topic of the possible vote rigging has also come to the
headline of the local press.
</P>
<P>
The Persian daily Salam urged Rafsanjani to firmly enforce
his sublime supervision over the process of the presidential
elections.
</P>
<P>
The Iranians are preparing to go to the polls in three days
in what is described by all observers here as the closest
election contest since the 1979 Islamic revolution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970521.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgarian Parliament Elects New Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria's parliament today approved
as prime minister, Ivan Kostov, the leader of the Union of
Democratic Forces (UDF).
</P>
<P>
Kostov won the nomination with 179 votes to 54, with no
abstentions.
</P>
<P>
Kostov, 48, was finance minister in the Dimiter Popov
government in 1991 and the Filip Dimitrov cabinet in 1992.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, Kostov, a former professor of economics, became head
of the UDF, which defeated the ruling Socialists and won the
legislative elections last April 19. 
</P>
