<HEADLINE> Peace Talks Between Manila, Muslim Rebels Extended </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Peacemakers from the Philippine
government and the rebel Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF)
today decided to extend their talks for another day to May 22.
</P>
<P>
The two-day talks held in Cotabato City, the southern
Philippines, should have ended today. However, the two sides had
not yet reached consensus on the issues being discussed.
</P>
<P>
Foremost in their agenda is the repositioning of troops in
Buldon, Maguindanao, where the situation has remained tense since
a number of clashes occurred earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
Reports said government troops and MILF rebels in Buldon are
only separated by some 400 meters away from each other.
</P>
<P>
Professor Monir Bajunaid, acting chair of the MILF cessation of
hostilities committee, said, "The talks are moving slowly but
surely to peace."
</P>
<P>
"As long as we maintain this momentum, we are optimistic that
we will reach into something," he added.
</P>
<P>
Bajunaid said the two sides decided to extend their meeting for
another day due to "some points of contention which they would
like to resolve." 
