<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Kinshasa Jubilant at Kabila's Arrival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KINSHASA, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Kinshasa, capital of the
newly-born Democratic Republic of Congo, was permeated with a
jubilant atmosphere this morning as citizens turned out to
welcome its "liberator", Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
News spread throughout the teeming city that Kabila, president
of the new republic who just arrived last night, would make a
public show the first time in the capital and might just as well
swear in his new national salvation government today.
</P>
<P>
Political maveouvres are at the hight of activities in the
capital among various political groups. "All of the former
opposition parties, even those which had gathered around Mobutu
during the old days, are trying to make contacts with Kabila and
his men to carve a niche in the new government," said a political
observer.
</P>
<P>
Kabila's troops of the Alliance of the Democratic Forces for
the Liberation of Congo-Zaire (ADFL) on May 17 captured the
teeming capital of Kinshasa to topple former president Mobutu
Sese Seko.
</P>
<P>
And Kabila proclaimed himself the new president on the same
day when Mobutu flew to Lome, Togo before seeking political
asylum in a not-yet-known destination.
</P>
<P>
Today, in the capital's two major hotels of Inter-Continental
and Memling, political figures, foreign journalists are in every
corner waiting for interview by Kabila and his men.
</P>
<P>
And Kabila, who has been staying at the residence of exiled
former prime minister Likulia Bolongo in suburban Kinshasa since
he arrived in the capital late last night, is still talking with
major political leaders and discussing the formation of his
"broad-based" national salvation government.
</P>
<P>
Everywhere in the street, "Kabila" is the only word on
everyone's lips.
</P>
<P>
"Everybody is talking about Kabila. What's he going to do to
govern the country? What's he going to do to unite all the ethnic
groups? What's he going to do to ensure peace and prosperity in
the warn-torn country? and above all, what's he going to do to
fight wide-spreading corruption?" said a political observer.
</P>
<P>
"We hope this man will give us a good life prospect," said a
poor single mother with four children.
</P>
<P>
"We are happy to see him here," said a local newspaper
peddler. "He brings us good business."
</P>
<P>
Kinshasa is the last major city in Africa's third largest
country "liberated" by Kabila army.
</P>
<P>
And three days after the entry of his army in the capital,
Kinshasa citizens were staying out the night waiting for
definitely something nice but not really knowing what it was
going to be like.
</P>
<P>
"He is welcomed because his army never looted civilians, as
Mobutu's army did," said an old man who lived throughout the
years ruled by Mobutu Sese Seko, the exiled Zairean president.
</P>
<P>
May 17 saw Kabila's well-disciplined troops marching along the
streets of the capital without doing any harm to local civilians
while many Kinshasa residents had suffered from a nightmare of
wide-scale looting carried out by soldiers of Mobutu's defeated
army.
</P>
<P>
Public security improved during the last couple of days as
Kabila sent more troops to Kinshasa and took severe measures to
crack down on looting and any other forms of criminal offenses.
</P>
<P>
"Kabila, Welcome to Kinshasa" is the headline carried by most
of today's local newspapers in the capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
