<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 09:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Rumors, Suspicion Spread Across </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Rumors and suspicion are spread
across Tehran, the capital of Iran, as the countdown of the 7th
presidential election is getting closer to May 23.
</P>
<P>
Tehran is now filled with various kinds of rumors and a strong
suspicion over the fairness of the tense election game, the vote
reading in particular.
</P>
<P>
A great number of eligible voters, including university
students, professors, bookshop keepers and taxi drivers, are
gossiping their worries over the possible vote rigging on coming
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Conservative Parliament Speaker Ali Akbar Nateq-Nouri and
open-minded former cultural and Islamic guidance minister
Mohammad Khatami are the two main contenders during the
presidential race.
</P>
<P>
The two rivals are represented by two major factions -- the
traditional and conservative camp backed by Iran's Supreme
Leader Ali Khamenei and the moderate and liberal camp supported
by President Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani.
</P>
<P>
Nateq-Nouri is facing powerful challenge from Khatami who is
gaining more and more support from the intellectual circles and
citizens in big cities.
</P>
<P>
A specialist predicted that Nateq-Nouri would win 60 percent
of the votes in rural areas and small cities while Khatami would
get 60 percent of the votes in big cities.
</P>
<P>
The victory of either presidential candidate would produce
different kind of political and economic impact upon the
political horizon in Iran.
</P>
<P>
That is why a great number of people with independent thinking
have been mobilized in the presidential election campaign in a bid
to have something new in the country.
</P>
<P>
Abbas Jaffari, a bookstore keeper in downtown Tehran, said that
vote rigging is not just rumor but it is a possible practice,
otherwise, President Rafsanjani would not touch upon the issue and
alarm the public of the imminent danger.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, Rafsanjani openly warned Interior Ministry
officials against any kinds of cheating at ballot boxes and called
for strict impartiality of election observers.
</P>
<P>
"Any effort to rig the elections should be seen as a grave
sin and inexcusable treason," he addressed large crowd of people
on the campus of Tehran University.
</P>
<P>
He noted that "the change of public votes would have very
negative impact on the society. The people will lose their trust
in the system. This treason will be unforgivable."
</P>
<P>
The severe warning by the 64-year-old president had brought
the speculation into the air across the country, which has been
widely spreading among people in various cities.
</P>
<P>
In response to Rafsanjani's statement, Ayatollah Ali Janati,
Secretary of the powerful Guardians Council, said Tuesday that any
violation of election rules by anyone must be countered
indiscriminately.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the seminar of supervising boards of the council
and inspectors of the Interior Ministry, he warned against going
beyond the limits in the elections and stressed that limits must
be observed.
</P>
<P>
"We are duty bound to prevent violations and counter
violators," he stressed, adding that the system is founded on
Islam and ethics.
</P>
<P>
He reminded the supervisory teams of their grave responsibility
in the process of elections and said "you are responsible for
healthy elections."
</P>
<P>
A political analyst noted that all supervisory teams are
dispatched by the Guardians Council and the Interior Ministry,
which are closely controlled by Khamenei.
</P>
<P>
Many supporters of Khatami accused the Guardians Council of
violating its neutrality in announcing the list of the four
candidates by putting Nateq-Nouri at the top of the list since
the normal practice in every election has been to cite the
candidates in alphabetical order. Listed in alphabetical order,
Nateq-Nouri would come last and Khatami first.
</P>
<P>
Iranians are preparing to go to the polls Friday in what is
described by all observers as the fiercest election contest since
the 1979 Islamic revolution.
</P>
<P>
The race is a crucial test for the Islamic rule and involves
an orderly transition of power from current President Rafsanjani
after two consecutive four-year terms to the new president.
</P>
<P>
Although Nateq-Nouri seems to be ahead of his top rival
Khatami, most political observers hold that the elections will go
to a second round. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
