<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pacific Basin Economic Council Meeting Ends in Manila </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The 30th International General
Meeting of the Pacific Basin Economic Council (PBEC) ended here
today with calls for the Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC)
to quickly implement its vision for the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
In a resolution adopted by the meeting, business leaders from
the Pacific area urged the APEC to "move in 1997 from an agenda
setting body to an implementing body."
</P>
<P>
They applauded APEC's vision for the region's economic and
trade cooperation and promised to work with the APEC to ensure
that tangible benefits are created for business and the region's
people.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also adopted two other resolutions on Hong Kong's
return to China and the expansion of the World Trade Organization
(WTO).
</P>
<P>
The PBEC supported all parties involved in the efforts toward
Hong Kong's smooth return to China and endorsed the WTO's
inclusion of all PBEC economies.
</P>
<P>
The three-day annual meeting also discussed many other issues,
including the challenges in adapting to the changing regional
business environment, barriers in liberalizing banking and
financial services, and pressures of population and urbanization.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice Premier Li Lanqing, Malaysian Deputy Prime
Minister Anwar Ibrahim and WTO Director General Renato Ruggiero
made keynote speeches at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was attended by over 600 businessmen leaders and
government officials from the PBEC's 20 member economies.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement at the end of the meeting, the next
two PBEC international meetings will be held in the Chilean
capital of Santiago in May 1998 and Hong Kong in 1999
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Founded in 1967, the PBEC is the region's oldest business
organization, which is composed of business leaders from more than
1,200 companies in the Pacific rim. It aims to promote the
expansion of trade and economic development through open markets.
</P>
<P>
PBEC member economies include Australia, Canada, Chile,
Ecuador, China, the United States, Russia, Colombia, Fiji, Hong
Kong, Indonesia, Japan, South Korea, Malaysia, Mexico, New
Zealand, Peru, the Philippines, Chinese Taipei and Thailand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
