<HEADLINE> Frechmen Killed, Causing Security Concerns in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KINSHASA, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Two French businessmen were
killed in Kinshasa by armed looters last night, three days after
Laurent Kabila's troops captured the Zairean capital.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses said today the killing occurred in the residential
areas in uptown Kinshasa as looters, believed to be soldiers of
the former government troops of exiled president Mobutu Sese
Seko, broke into their house and opened fire at them before they
robbed the valuables.
</P>
<P>
The looters fled and soldiers of Kabila's liberation army are
conducting investigations.
</P>
<P>
However, local residents said it is hardly possible to find
out the looters as many of Mobutu's soldiers went underground
with the arms after they were defeated by Kabila's troops.
</P>
<P>
Troops of the Alliance of the Democratic Forces for the
Liberation of Congo-Zaire (ADFL), led by Kabila, entered the
capital on May 17 without meeting much military resistence, only
to find many former soldiers of Mobutu's army fleeing with their
guns.
</P>
<P>
A large-scale looting occurred overnight that day in Kinshasa,
done by the defeated soldiers of Mobutu's army.
</P>
<P>
After that, Kabila sent more troops to the capital to boost the
security.
</P>
<P>
"The security is definitely improving. But these armed Mobutu
loyalists are causing big concerns over the public security in
Kinshasa," said a local Kinshasa resident.
</P>
<P>
Kabila later issued an order for the former government troops
to lay down their arms.
</P>
<P>
Some of Mobutu's soldiers did shift their stance and joined
Kabila's liberation army, but most of the Mobutu men were
rejected. Some were even arrested for their bad records in
killing Kabila's men and looting the civilians.
</P>
<P>
"That's why they looted again and fled," said a foreign
diplomat in Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
"There are simply too many of them in Kinshasa today," said
local residents.
</P>
<P>
During the night, despite the lift of curfew, there is nobody
in the street, except a couple of Kabila's soldiers here and
there at some strategic places in the capital.
</P>
<P>
"Take good care of your life and property," that's the advise
provided to foreigners, especially journalists, by many foreign
embassies in Kinshasa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
