<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 12:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Defense Minister: Iran Continues Arming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The Lebanese Muslim militia
Hezbollah has been receiving large quantities of arms and
ammunition from Iran by air via Syria in the past few months,
Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai has revealed.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio today quoted the defense minister as saying that
Israel was examining reports that these arms to the fundamentalist
guerrilla may have included improved, long-range Katyusha rockets.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai made the remarks during a visit Tuesday to the
Israeli self-styled security zone of 1,000 square kilometers in
south Lebanon, where he was briefed by senior officers, including
Northern Command Amiram Levine and Israeli army commander in
Lebanon Eli Amitai.
</P>
<P>
His visit came amid a marked escalation of fightings. On Monday
morning, a suicide bomber, from Lebanese militia of the Amal
Movement, attempted to destroy an Israeli Navy gunboat. In a clash
north of the buffer zone last Thursday night, three paratroopers
were killed and seven other soldiers wounded.
</P>
<P>
"There is a constant air activity, which I have remarked upon
many times, of planes flying in equipment and weapons from Iran to
Damascus (of Syria) and from there to the Bekaa Valley and to
Lebanon," Mordechai said.
</P>
<P>
"Some of this equipment is for civilian needs, and some for
military requirements, which includes anti-tank weapons,
ammunition, arms, and a variety of different equipment in order to
give Hezbollah and other terrorist organizations on Lebanese soil
better fighting capabilities."
</P>
<P>
Mordechai said he was investigating reports that the weapons
flied to Syria may have included Katyusha rockets with a
long-range capability that would theoretically enable them to
reach the beach areas at the Israeli northern coastal city of
Haifa.
</P>
<P>
He accused Iran of giving Hezbollah financial and military
aid, as well as ideological backing, and charged Syria with
aiding the anti-Israeli militant group. Nevertheless, Mordechai
reiterated his call to Syria to return to the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai visited an outpost in "the security zone" and later
an observation point on top of the joint headquarters of
Israel's client militia South Lebanese Army in south Lebanon,
and the Israeli army's Lebanese liaison unit.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that initiated military operations, in which the
Israeli army had scored what he termed as some notable successes
in the past two months, would continue.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah, which is allegedly backed by Iran ideologically,
economically and militarily, frequently launches cross border
attacks against the northern part of the Jewish state to fight
the Israeli occupation of south Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
