<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Buddhist Followers Celebrate Buddha's Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of Buddhist followers
gathered at the Guangji Temple here today to mark Visakha, or the
Buddha's Day.
</P>
<P>
Visakha, a full moon celebration in May, is held by Buddhist
believers in most countries and regions including those belonging
to the Tibetan and Pali-language family in China. They believe
that the Buddha was born, received his Enlightenment, and passed
away on the full-moon day in May.
</P>
<P>
The Buddhist followers belonging to Chinese-language family,
however, hold every Eighth day of April in lunar calendar (or
seven days before Visakha) as the birthday of the Buddha.
</P>
<P>
Responding to advocacy by Zhao Puchu, chairman of the Chinese
Association of Buddhism, the Chinese Buddhist followers also began
in 1990 to hold rites on Visakha. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
