<HEADLINE> Nagano Winter Games' Downhill Course Shortened </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 21 (Xinhua) -- 1998 Nagano Winter Olympic Games will
see the shortest downhill skiing course in the Olympic history,
Makoto Kobayashi, director general of the Nagano organising
committee (NAOC) said on Wednesday in Monaco.
</P>
<P>
The International Olympic Committee (IOC) and the International
Ski Federation (FIS) dropped demands to extend the downhill run
due to environmental concerns.
</P>
<P>
Makoto Kobayashi said that the Japanese authorities made clear
their opposition to raising the start of the course in view of
environmental considerations while the IOC and the FIS are no
longer questioning them on this subject. "It's finished," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Nagano run, 2,923 meters for the men and 2,654 meters for
the women, will be around a third shorter than any other downhill
in the history of the Winter Games. The start is at 1,680 meters
altitude, and has a drop of 840 meters, with an average run
expected to take just 90 seconds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970521.0126 </DOCNO>
