<HEADLINE> Banks Push Australian Share Market to Fresh Records </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market set
fresh records today, with banking stocks back in the limelight
following the U.S. Federal Reserve's decision last night to leave
interest rates unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries posted new highs across the day before
closing 12.5 points stronger and just 0.3 points off its best at a
record 2,543.2.
</P>
<P>
"The big news today was no rate rise out of the United States
and that was the impetus for a decent performance locally,"
Austock's David Perry said.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index climbed 31.7 points to 3,933.3 while
the all resources slipped 4.2 to 1,480.7.
</P>
<P>
Banking stocks clawed back some of their recent losses to firm
83.3 points, or 1.92 percent, to 4,432.9.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank led the charge, adding 38.3 cents to
18.183 Australian dollar on volume of 3.08 million shares, while
ANZ recovered 33 cents to 8.19 Australian dollars ahead of next
Wednesday's interim results.
</P>
<P>
Westpac Bank was up nine to 7.17 Australian dollars on volume
of 3.95 million and Commonwealth Bank closed eight stronger at
13.83 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Macqauaire Bank was strong among the regions, surging 25 cents
to 9.20 Australian dollars, St George climbed nine to 7.93
Australian dollars and Bank of Melbourne gained one to 9.32
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover reached 390.4 million shares, valued at 1.01
billion Australian dollars (784.2 million U.S. dollars), with
rises outpacing falls 606 to 445 and 467 issues steady.
</P>
<P>
The gold index was slightly weaker, losing 1.2 points to
1,542.9, with gold bullion closing at 343.10 U.S. dollars an ounce
from 342.00 U.S. dollars last.  
</P>
</TEXT>
