<DOCNO> XIE19970521.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> W. Africa States to Jointly Crack Down on Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 21 (Xinhua) -- West African countries are
determined to evolve strategies aimed at stamping out the
increasing crime wave in the sub-region.
</P>
<P>
As a first step forward, the Nigerian police has set out to
negotiate with neighboring Benin to control cross-border
crimes, according to the country's Police Inspector-General Alhaji
Ibrahim Coomassie.
</P>
<P>
Criminal activities, especially cross-border crimes, have been on
the rise since the signing of a protocal among West African countries
to facilitate free movement of goods and persons years ago.
</P>
<P>
Criminals take advantage of the protocol to traverse borders for
refuge while perpetrating such crimes as car theft, robbery and
illicit trafficking of drug, fire-arms and art works.
</P>
<P>
The situation has aroused concern among sub-regional leaders.
Nigeria's head of state General Sani Abacha has said that with such
crimes quickly gaining ground in the sub-region, no country is now
safe from the activities.
</P>
<P>
To jointly combat the crimes, two sub-regional committees have
been set up among member countries of the Economoic Community of
West African States, now chaired by General Abacha.
</P>
<P>
The committees are mandated to harmonize legal instruments of
coopertion and design modalities for training and operation.
</P>
<P>
In Nigeria, the government said it would continue to work
out ways and supply appropriate equipment to fight perpetrators of
violent crimes in the country despite the big cost of crime
prevention.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
