<DOCNO> XIE19970521.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Cases Doubling Every 14 Months in India: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Cases of acquired immuno
deficiency syndrome (AIDS) are doubling every 14 months in India
and infection with the AIDS virus has become widespread among
young men and women in the lower socio-economic class in the
country, the Press Trust of India (PTI) quoted a report as saying
today.
</P>
<P>
From 1987 to 1990, there were an average of 5.7 AIDS cases each
year at the National AIDS Reference Center at Christian medical
college hospital, Vellore in Tamil Nadu and these shot up to 28
per year from 1991 to 1993 and 104 in 1994, said the report of the
college researchers in the Indian journal of medical research.
</P>
<P>
When the data from only Vellore, the headquarters of Tamil
Nadu's North Arcot district with a population of 3 million, is
extrapolated to the entire population of the country, it indicates
that there would have been at least 25,361 AIDS cases in India by
the end of 1994. This figure tallies with the World Health
Organization's projections of 20,000 AIDS cases in India by the
end of 1993, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Most of the 211 patients diagnosed were young men and women
between 31 and 33 years, belonging to the lower socio-economic
class in the country, the report added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
