<DOCNO> XIE19970521.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan, Macao Establish Joint Logistic Venture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, May 21 (Xinhua) -- A local transportation company in
Macao today signed an agreement with a Japanese logistic company
to establish a joint logistic venture in Macao.
</P>
<P>
The I-JCM, Logistic (Macao) Ltd., will be jointly established
with Integrated Group, a Japanese-funded company based in
Malaysia, holding 60 percent shares, and a local cargo ship
company, JCM, holding 40 percent shares.
</P>
<P>
Based in Macao, the new company will try to explore the
potential of Macao as a free shipping entrepot in the Pearl River
Delta and the Southeast Asia region, said Eric Yeung, chairman of
the I-JCM.
</P>
<P>
Makoto Takahashi, managing director of Integrated Logistic (HK)
Ltd., said at the signing ceremony that he believes Macao will
enjoy growing business of logistic services.
</P>
<P>
"Macao can become a logistic hub of south China," he said. "It
is one of the important gateways to China's inland areas. A lot of
foreign manufacturers have established factories in Zhuhai and
other major cities in the southern China region, and the new
airport in Macao will become much important than before."
</P>
<P>
The new joint venture marks a milestone that Japanese
investment ever entered Macao in logistic business. It came into
being after 18 months of preparation.
</P>
<P>
The Integrated Group, established in 1973, now has branches in
Hong Kong and Shenzhen city. Its main customers include the
leading Japanese electric appliances producers like National,
Sharp, Hitachi and Sony.
</P>
<P>
The company's business scope ranges from transportation,
shipping, consultation and warehousing.
</P>
<P>
The local partner of the business, JCM, was established in
early 1996 by 17 Macao ventures, most engaged in foreign
trade. Shareholders of JCM holds about half of the export volume
in Macao. 
</P>
</TEXT>
