<HEADLINE> HK Police Force Remains Part of Interpol: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Police Force will
remain a part of the Interpol after Hong Kong's handover but will
operate as a sub-bureau of China instead of being a sub-bureau of
Britain, according to Hong Kong's Commissioner of Police Eddie Hui
Ki-on.
</P>
<P>
Hui made the comment when addressing delegates at a recent
Interpol meeting of Asian contact officers here.
</P>
<P>
Hui said that apart from a few superficial and cosmetic
changes, there would be no disruption to the force's work and no
change to the way in which the Hong Kong Police Force carries it
out.
</P>
<P>
"The rank and organizational structure will remain as it is
today and the force will retain the sole responsibility for
internal security and the policing of Hong Kong - including its
waters and border with the Chinese mainland.
</P>
<P>
"With regard to myself as Commissioner of police, I shall be
responsible to the Chief Executive of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region," Hui said.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong's future is guaranteed by the Sino-British Joint
Declaration, which is an internationally accepted agreement. I am
confident that Hong Kong will continue to prosper, that law and
order will be steadfastly maintained and that the relationships
with overseas law enforcement agencies which the Hong Kong Police
have developed in the past will be maintained," said ACP Crime
Wong.
</P>
<P>
Hu Xin, Interpol delegate from China, said that "As with the
rest of the officers from various Asian Interpol bureaus, we look
forward to working with Interpol Hong Kong in the future as we
have done in the past. Our communication in terms of the exchange
of information on criminals and crime will only get better."
</P>
<P>
Mohammad Zahid Mahmood, chairman of the conference, said, "If
any of the 29 Interpol delegates from the 17 Asian countries
(regions) represented during the meeting had any doubts as to what
the post handover Interpol Hong Kong would be like, we go away
with confidence that in the future for the Hong Kong Police and
its Interpol Bureau, it's basically business as usual. And in
terms of fighting international crime, that's a very good news."
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong joined the Interpol in 1960 and Hong Kong Police
officers regularly attended conferences organized by Interpol.
</P>
<P>
The Asian Contact Officer Network was set up in 1995 to provide
the structure for urgent and effective personal contact between
Asian National Central Bureaus (each member state in Interpol is
represented by a National Central Bureau) and a sub-bureau.
</P>
</TEXT>
