<DOCNO> XIE19970521.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia to Cut 1997-98 Immigrant Intake by 6,000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Australia would cut immigrant
intake by 6,000 next year to 68,000, Immigration Minister Philip
Ruddock said in Melbourne today.
</P>
<P>
Ruddock said the federal government was forced to reduce the
migrant intake for 1997-98 to 68,000, down from the previous
year's 74,000, by continuing high unemployment and the number of
migrants who had featured in unemployment figures in the past.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Associated Press said the figure represents a
drop of 20 percent over the past two years.
</P>
<P>
The humanitarian and refugee intake will remain at 12,000,
taking the total immigration intake to 80,000.
</P>
<P>
Ruddock said surveys had shown that many unskilled migrants who
had entered under the former government's guidelines, largely in
family reunion categories, had been unable to find work.
</P>
<P>
It was not in the national interest to continue to allow large
numbers into the country, he said.
</P>
<P>
The immigration minister insists the cut is not a response to
independent MP Pauline Hanson, who called for an end to immigrant
intake and said the nation risked being swamped by Asians in her
maiden speech to the parliament last September.
</P>
<P>
"If there were a response to Pauline Hanson there would
probably be no program at all," Ruddock said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the government's refugee guidelines favored
people who had no place to go, and those applying from the former
Yugoslavia and the Middle East would receive top priority, while
those seeking admission in the same category next year from Asian
and African countries would be assigned a lesser priority.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970521.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Personal Savings in China Hit Record High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Savings continue to be a major
investment in China and topped the four trillion yuan (about 480
billion US dollars) mark by the end of March.
</P>
<P>
According to the People's Bank of China, the central bank,
Chinese had 4.15 trillion yuan in savings deposits at that time,
up 23.7 percent from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
A total of 277.6 billion yuan in personal savings was added in
the first three months, including 197.7 billion yuan in fixed-term
deposits.
</P>
<P>
The large proportion of new fixed-term deposits demonstrates
the stability of these deposits despite two interest rate cuts
last year, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
They note that a stable increase in the total amount of
personal savings, although at a lower rate than in past years,
indicates that the public are confident about macro-economic
controls and future economic development.  
</P>
</TEXT>
