<HEADLINE> Colombia Decides to Set up Demilitarized Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, May 20 (Xinhua) -- Colombian President
Ernesto Samper said today that the government has decided to set
up a demilitarized zone in the southern province of Caqueta in
which the guerillas can free 70 government troops they captured
last year.
</P>
<P>
The 13,200-square-kilometer zone is located along the Caguan
river, Samper said at a ceremony held in the presidential office.
</P>
<P>
The government will cease all military actions and police
patrol in the zone during the 32 days as from May 23 so that the
Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia (FARC) can release the 70
soldiers under the monitoring of the International Red Cross
Society, announced Samper.
</P>
<P>
The president hoped that the guerillas will take the
government's decision, made after Monday's meeting between the
president and a number of ministers and top military leaders, as a
gesture for peace and rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
The 70 soldiers were seized in an attack by FARC, the country's
largest guerrilla group, on a government military camp in the
southern province of Putumayo on August 30, 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
