<HEADLINE> Increasing Overseas Investment in East China Development Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANTAI, May 21 (Xinhua) -- More than 40 million US dollars of
overseas investment have flowed into the Yantai Development Zone
in this east Chinese city in Shandong Province during the first
quarter of the year.
</P>
<P>
The three-month period saw 730 million yuan in output value
from overseas-funded businesses in the zone, a 40 percent rise
from the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The zone has attracted overseas investment from 27 countries
and regions, including the US, Britain, France, Germany, Japan,
the ROK, and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-four overseas-financed enterprises are adding more than
200 million yuan worth of investment, and there are now 38
overseas-funded projects with an investment of more than 10
million US dollars each.
</P>
<P>
The zone will obtain an increasing amount of foreign funds from
multinational companies in east Asia, Europe, and America. But it
is not encouraging low-technology, high-consumption, or
environment-unfriendly foreign-funded projects, or those with an
investment of less than 100 US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Construction of a 7.9 billion-yuan automobile parts project
funded by the ROK's Daewoo Company is expected to begin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
