<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Major Bank to Extend More Housing Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The China Construction Bank, the
country's major bank for fixed-asset investment loans, will extend
more loans to potential home buyers, according to a senior bank
official.
</P>
<P>
The amount of money for home buyer loans this year will go up
by four billion yuan (about 480 million US dollars), the bank's
vice-governor, Shi Chungui, says.
</P>
<P>
Shi also said that in the future 50 percent of CCB's new loans
for fixed assets will be extended to home buyers.
</P>
<P>
CCB became the first Chinese bank to finance home buying in the
late 1980s, and by the end of last year, had extended a total of
20 billion yuan worth of such loans, 6.51 billion yuan of that
outstanding.
</P>
<P>
In Shanghai, China's leading economic center, the amount of
outstanding home loans with the bank is 2.3 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
As China reforms its old housing system, where apartments are
allotted to workers for nominal amounts of rent, more individuals
are buying their own houses. One problem however, has been that a
bank loan is essential for most people because their income almost
always falls far short of that needed for the price of a new
house.  
</P>
</TEXT>
