<DOCNO> XIE19970521.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Most Hygienic Port </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QINHUANGDAO, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Qinhuangdao on China's northeast
coast has become known as a hygienic port after making efforts to
curb pollution in the past decade.
</P>
<P>
Local environmental protection departments report that smog
and coal dust in the air at Qinhuangdao are strictly controlled,
even though it is considered the world's biggest handler of energy
production materials.
</P>
<P>
The offshore water at Qinhuangdao Port now also meets China's
national quality standards for the offshore water.
</P>
<P>
The port has 38 berths handling from 3,000 dead weight tonnage
(dwt) to 50,000 dwt, along 11.3 km of the northeastern coast, and
covering an area of 9.2 sq km.
</P>
<P>
In the past ten years, the port has spent 120 million yuan on
treating pollution, and adding environmental protection facilities
to every port projects.
</P>
<P>
The port administration has drawn up rules and regulations in
accordance with national environmental protection laws, and has
linked prevention and treatment of pollution from coal and smog
dust or petroleum to workers' bonuses to ensure success.
</P>
<P>
The efforts have not only created a better environment for over
60,000 people working and living in this energy distribution and
collection port, but have also helped protect neighboring scenic
sites such as the beach at the Beidaihe Summer Resort and Shanhai
Pass.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
