<HEADLINE> Tanzanians Call for Equality in World Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Lecturers of the University
of Dar es Salaam have called on western countries to allow equal
partnership in the modern global trade, local press reported
today.
</P>
<P>
They made the call during a public lecture on "Globalization,
Africa and New Realities" by visiting Swedish Secretary of State
from the Ministry of Foreign Affairs Mats Karlsson here at the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
Ruth Meena, an expert, said that it was time for Africa to
demand an equal play field on global trade and partnership if
such developments are for the mutual benefit of both sides.
</P>
<P>
She called on the developed countries to allow a revision of
the terms of trade and partnership with Africa because currently
it is the rich states that dictate and dominate the unfair
relations while the poor have been forced to liberalize their
economies.
</P>
<P>
Anna Tibajiuka, the head of the Tanzania Women's Council,
challenged the controversial World Trade Organization (WTO) to
enforce equality in the global trade and partnership rather than
pressing Africa to unfairly open up its economies.
</P>
<P>
She noted that Africa has virtually lost its confidence in
global trade and partnership due to the prevailing inequality.
</P>
<P>
Samuel Wangwe, the Economic and Social Research Foundation
(ESF) Director, said as Africa has no choice to play a role it
wants in modern globalization, both donors and recipients of
development aid are bad players.
</P>
<P>
In response, Karlsson said it was true that Africa has for a
long time been unfairly treated in the global trade, citing the
barbaric exploitation done by the west during the slavery, colonia
and modern era.
</P>
<P>
He noted, however, that the fate of Africa's demands for
equality in globalization depends first on Africans themselves.
</P>
<P>
The current cooperation between the South and the North has a
flawed base which demands renovation so as to get rid of
post-colonial structures, he said.
</P>
<P>
The lecture was part of a continental debate on Swedish
African policy's reshaping as Africa is due to enter into another
trade partnership agreement with Europe after the Lome Convention
expires in February 2000.  enditem

=05210835

=05210843
NNNN
16:44 16:44 g # PAB
</P>
