<HEADLINE> Former Colombian President Barco Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, May 20 (Xinhua) -- Former Colombian
president Virgilio Barco Vargas today died of stomach cancer and
Alzheimer's disease at the age of 75 in a Bogota clinic.
</P>
<P>
President Ernesto Samper expressed his condolence over Barco's
death in a radio broadcast.
</P>
<P>
"I share the sense of loss that all Colombians are
feeling. Barco was a man of few but firm convictions and very
dedicated to certain principles," said Samper.
</P>
<P>
The government of his home province of Norte de Santander
declared three days of mourning.
</P>
<P>
Barco, a Liberal Party member like Samper, started his
four-year presidency in May 1986 after a landslide victory in
elections.
</P>
<P>
Barco, who was born in 1921 in the northeast town of Cucuta on
the border with Venezuela, is widely remembered as one of the
capital's best-ever mayors for pushing forward a series of major
public works and urban renovation programs during his term between
1966 and 1969.
</P>
<P>
He served as Minister of Public Works and Minister of
Agriculture in the late 1950s and early 1960s.
</P>
<P>
The ex-president partly succeeded in defusing Colombia's
long-running guerrilla war by striking a peace treaty with the
leftist M-19 guerrilla group and opening the way for former
guerrillas to return to civilian life. 
</P>
</TEXT>
