<HEADLINE> Nyanza Area Tops on HIV-Positive Mothers in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Nyanza Province of Kenya has the
highest number of expectant mothers who have tested HIV positive
in the country, according to a senior medical officer.
</P>
<P>
Nyanza Provincial Medical Officer of Health Richard Muga told
a one-day seminar that 20-30 percent of expectant mothers in
Kisumu, the provincial capital, were carriers of HIV, which
causes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
The Kenya Times newspaper today quoted Provincial Commissioner
Joseph Kaguthi as saying at the seminar that the province
recorded 16,000 cases of HIV/AIDS in 1996, accounting for 20
percent of the total in the country.
</P>
<P>
Currently, he said, 45 percent of hospital beds in the
province are occupied by HIV positive people or AIDS patients.
</P>
<P>
Roselyne Onyuka, Provincial Director of Education, told the
participants of the seminar that more than 2,700 teachers died
every year of AIDS-related disease in the province.
</P>
<P>
Muhoroni Sugar Company Managing Director E.O. Wanga noted on
the same occasion that 90 percent of the company's staff deaths
were AIDS-related.
</P>
<P>
Muga pointed out that 75 percent of the victims got the
disease through sex,
</P>
<P>
The seminar was resolved that inter-sectoral HIV/AIDS
committees at district, divisional and locational levels be formed
to help create awareness among the local people at the
grassroots.
</P>
<P>
According to Onyuka, the Kenyan Ministry of Education is
intensifying awareness activities and counselling among the
people to help combat the spread of the disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
