<DOCNO> XIE19970521.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Ratifies WTO Agreement on Government Procurement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong today formally signed
the World Trade Organization (WTO) Agreement on Government
Procurement, according to a Hong Kong government spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The provisions of the agreement will enter into force in Hong
Kong after 30 days, i.e., June 19, 1997, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Agreement on Government Procurement (GPA) provides for a
set of rules that govern the procurement of goods and services by
government and other public entities of signatories.
</P>
<P>
It lays down very detailed rules on tendering procedures,
technical specifications and challenge procedures.
</P>
<P>
The objective of the agreement is to ensure foreign products
and suppliers can compete on the level playing field with domestic
products and suppliers for public procurement contracts.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's application to join the agreement was unanimously
agreed by signatories to the agreement on December 5, 1996.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said: "We were given a six-month period to align
our domestic procedures with the provisions of the agreement. We
have now completed the alignment process, and are ready to
participate in the agreement."
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong maintain an open and fair procurement regime. Our
accession to the GPA, therefore, will not incur significant
additional obligations on current parties.
</P>
<P>
"Joining the GPA will enhance confidence in our procurement
regime and improve access of our goods and services to the
government procurement markets of other World Trade Organization
GPA signatories," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Apart from government departments, statutory bodies, namely,
the Urban Council, Regional Council, Hospital Authority, Housing
Authority, Airport Authority, Mass Transit Railway Corporation,
and Kowloon-Canton Railway Corporation, will also be subject to
the rules provided under the agreement which governs the
procurement of goods, services and construction works above
certain specified contract values.
</P>
<P>
Signatories to the agreement are Canada, the European
Communities, Israel, Aruba/Netherlands, Japan, South Korea,
Norway, Switzerland, and the United States.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
