<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southwest Chinese City Doubles Quarterly Income Tax Revenues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Personal income tax revenues of
this capital city of southwest China's Sichuan Province doubled in
the first quarter of this year, the city's local tax bureau
reports.
</P>
<P>
It says that the rapid growth follows a 67 percent increase in
individual income tax revenues last year. The bureau declines to
reveal the exact amount collected between January and March.
</P>
<P>
The fact that more employers are willing to deduct income taxes
from their employees' wages on behalf of the tax agencies is a
major reason for the rapid revenue increases.
</P>
<P>
Taxes collected this way now account for more than 90 percent
of total tax revenues, official figures show.
</P>
<P>
Increased efforts to curb tax evasion among high-income
earners, such as lawyers, taxi drivers, chefs, beauticians,
entertainers and advertisers have also helped the stable growth in
revenues.
</P>
<P>
A tax check done among these people netted more
than 20 million yuan (about 2.4 million US dollars) in individual
income taxes last year, the official says.  
</P>
</TEXT>
