<HEADLINE> New Fertilizer Applying Technique Raises Timber Output </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Scientists in China recently
successfully developed a fertilizer applying technique that is
used to raise the timber output of low-productive species across
the country.
</P>
<P>
A survey conducted in more than 300 experiment spots in 14
provinces or autonomous regions shows that this technique can
increase the output of timber by 15 to 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to Shen Guofang, a member of the Chinese Academy of
Sciences, who heads the research, this technique will
significantly reduce the time needed for young trees to grow into
useful timber.
</P>
<P>
The technique was jointly developed by nine institutes
including the Chinese Academy of Forestry Sciences.
</P>
<P>
The fertilizer applying technique has reportedly been used in
the World Bank-funded National Afforestation Project, and has
yielded 350 million yuan (some 43 million US dollars) in economic
benefits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
