<HEADLINE> Telephone to Every Household in Quanzhou </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, May 21 (Xinhua) -- All rural households have installed
telephone in some 100 villages in Quanzhou, a city in east China's
Fujian Province, becoming China's first group of villages with 100
percent telephone ownership.
</P>
<P>
Local farmers use the telephone to get market information and
contact businesses. As one village head said. phone service is an
important part of the local investment environment: "No telephone
means bad image in the eyes of investors."
</P>
<P>
All of 10,000-odd households in Chendi Town have installed
telephones. Rural enterprises witnessed fast growth for years in
Chendi, which became China's first town whose telephone coverage
reached 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
To boost telephone use, local telecom authorities have made
efforts to lay more lines while reducing the cost for installation
and line rental.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970521.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tourist Arrivals to East Asia, Pacific Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 21 (Xinhua) -- International tourist arrivals to
East Asia and the Pacific region climbed by a healthy 9.3 percent
in 1996 to top 87 million.
</P>
<P>
A report from the World Tourism Organization stated that
earnings from international tourism in the region kept pace with
the growth in arrivals, increasing by 9.8 percent to 81 billion US
dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
The Executive Council of the World Tourism Organization is now
holding its 55th session meeting here as a prelude to the World
Tourism Leaders' Meeting scheduled on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The overall buoyancy of the economies of East Asia and the
Pacific is reflected in the region's strong tourism growth last
year," the report quoted Francesco Frangialli, Secretary-General
of the organization as saying.
</P>
<P>
Among the region's fastest growing destinations last year were
Indonesia, Macao and Japan, the report said.
</P>
<P>
In terms of receipts from international tourism, the biggest
increases in East Asia and the Pacific last year were garnered by
Japan, Australia, Indonesia and China.
</P>
<P>
The WTO report predicts that tourism in East Asia and the
Pacific will grow by an average of 7.6 percent annually to the
year 2000, when the region is expected to attract 229 million
tourists a year or one out of every five tourists in the world.
</P>
<P>
Limits and constraints that could possibly hold back the
region's tourism boom include airport congestion and shortages of
investment capital to finance new infrastructure, as well as lack
of trained staff and price hikes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970521.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xiamen City Intensifies Combat against Narcotics-related Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Coastal Xiamen City in east China's
Fujian Province has taken severe measures to crack down upon
drug-trafficking over the past several years, local police sources
said.
</P>
<P>
From 1993 to 1996, police cracked 401 drug trafficking cases
and destroyed one "ice" drug processing plant, seizing 44.69 kg of
heroin, 48.6 kg of "ice" drug, 27.46 kg of opium, and a large
amount of other narcotics.
</P>
<P>
Altogether 666 people were found involved in drug-trafficking,
and 502 were sentenced to prison terms.
</P>
<P>
Xiamen is a major port city leading to Hong Kong, Macao, and
Taiwan, so drug traffickers have used the city as a good transit
site since it was designated as a special economic zone a dozen
years ago, local police sources said.
</P>
<P>
Public security departments in the city also put emphasis on
raiding places where drugs are taken, especially small hotels,
rented houses, and dancing and singing halls. From 1993 to 1996,
police busted into 296 places and seized 937 narcotics takers.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the city established a rehabilitation center in
October 1993, which has since offered treatment for 593 drug
addicts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970521.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangdong's Industry Continues Upward Trend </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Guangzhou, the capital city of
South China's Guangdong province, reports a steady improvement in
industrial performance, with total output value in the first
four months of this year reaching 53.98 billion yuan (6.7 billion
US dollars), up 15.22 percent over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The production and sales ratio increased to 96.13 prcent, up
by 0.68 percentage point compared with the first four months of
last year.
</P>
<P>
The increas of export is the major factor that has driven
forward the city's industrial development. In the first four
months of this year, the city exported 15.4 billion yuan (1.86
billion US dollars) worth of industrial products, up 28.3
percent over the same 1996 period.
</P>
<P>
Export volume now takes up 21.48 percent of the total
industrial output, which, experts believe, shows that enterprises
and overseas businessmans have come to fit into the new situation
since the export tax rate was twice reduced by the State.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics, overseas-funded enterprises are
performing relatively better than the state-owned and collective
ones in the city, and light industries are developing faster than
heavy industries.
</P>
<P>
Experts believe that the upward trend will continue in the
next couple of months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
