<HEADLINE> Unauthorized Border Check Points Banned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The southern Chinese autonomous
region of Guangxi is trying to put a halt to the flow of small
amount of goods that cross its borders by paying a certain
"tariff" that is charged at unauthorized check points where there
are no customs officers.
</P>
<P>
But now, border trade goods must go through normal customs
procedures or will be taken as smuggled goods, according to a
recent circular issued by the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous regional
government.
</P>
<P>
"We should firmly guard against the wrong practice since it not
only contravenes State customs regulations but also encourages
smuggling," provincial authorities say.
</P>
<P>
Guangxi has seen a sharp increase in its border trade with
neighboring Viet Nam in recent years. 
</P>
