<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Enterprises Help Bring Agriculture To High Level </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, May 21 (Xinhua) -- As increasing numbers of
Chinese enterprises develop markets in rural areas, more farmers
are becoming market-oriented as a result.
</P>
<P>
North China's Hebei Province is an example. More than 30
percent of its major farm produce and by-products are processed
and 62 percent are commercialized. And nearly four million of its
farmers compete in the market.
</P>
<P>
Shijiazhuang Sanlu Dairy Products Corporation produced more
than 470 million yuan in output value last year, relying on
abundant farm products. It has brought 63 dairy farms to
prosperity, involving 3,100 households of more than 5,000 farmers,
whose per-capita income rose to 2,600 yuan last year.
</P>
<P>
More enterprises have followed suit. And 1,000 key
agriculture-related enterprises are doing well, with 24 of them
each yielding over 100 million yuan worth of annual sales.
</P>
<P>
The province will increase this number to 2,000 by the end of
the century, and 20 of them are expected to sell products worth of
500 million yuan annually.
</P>
<P>
Hebei has set up more than 100 production bases of about 1.33
million ha in 60-plus counties, in a bid to link small production
to the big market.
</P>
<P>
Local farmers are doing a better job thanks to guidance from
enterprises concerned, and earning more accordingly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
