<HEADLINE> India Holding Talks with Neighbors on Wildlife </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 21 (Xinhua) -- India is holding serious talks
with its neighboring countries to help check illegal wildlife
trade activities, a government official said here today.
</P>
<P>
A memorandum of understanding (MOU) has already been signed
between India and Nepal for checking the trans-boundary movement
of wildlife.
</P>
<P>
Under the MOU, India's Forest Department officials have been
asked to sensitize the customs and border security force personnel
on the trade of medicinal plants, timber and animal parts.
</P>
<P>
The talks are going on between India and China on protection of
wildlife, the official said.
</P>
<P>
He said that India is also engaged in negotiations with Russia,
which focus on protection of the endangered bird species that pass
through the country during their annual migration.
</P>
<P>
The Myanmar region has emerged as the latest trade route
causing concern. Tiger parts and medicinal plants are being
smuggled through this region. This will be taken up at the next
meeting of the Convention on International Trade of Endangered
Species (CITES), the same official said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
