<HEADLINE> Neolithic Site Discovered In Southwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Human remains, pottery, and shell
and stoneware from the Late Stone Age have been discovered at
excavations in Yongning county in southwest China's Guangxi Zhuang
Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Eighteen human skeletons have been found. Those buried single
were found with funerary items like pottery, shell knives, stone
axes, arrowheads, and animal bones.
</P>
<P>
No such items were found in a large burial room containing
eight skeletons belonging to people of different ages.
</P>
<P>
The find suggests a hierarchical tribal system, Chinese
archaeologists say. They expect to excavate a 4,000-sq.m. area at
the site in five to seven years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
