<DOCNO> XIE19970521.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Businessmen Urge India to Lift Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi business leaders urged
India to remove all barriers to narrow the growing trade gap
between the two neighboring countries, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Bangladeshi businessmen had not been able to fully explore and
exploit the Indian market in the past due to the presence of a
number of non-tariff barriers, hidden subsidies and other policy
variables in India, said Abdullah Harun, president of the
Federation of Bangladesh Chambers of Commerce and Industry
(FBCCI).
</P>
<P>
"To create a level-playing field, non-tariff barriers on all
commodities should be dismantled and all commodities should be
dismantled on an urgent basis," he told a meeting of the
India-Bangladesh Joint Business Council (JBC) held here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The one-day council meeting ended with an agreement, in which
both sides agreed on an action plan towards expanding bilateral
trade and cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, both sides recommended further trade
liberalization while adopting fast track approach for tariff
concessions to rectify trade imbalance and curb unofficial trade.
</P>
<P>
A joint statement, issued by the two sides after the fourth
meeting of the council, also recommended encouraging and
legalizing border trade, making adequate administrative machinery
available at major points of the Bangladesh-India border.
</P>
<P>
The Indian side, led by Mumtaz Ahmed, who is also Chairman of
the JBC Council, said that Bangladesh should opt for selling its
services by allowing Indian traders to use its roads, waterway and
ports to fill up the gap in trade.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics showed a wide trade gap in the 1995-96
fiscal year with India's exports of 1.1 billion U.S. dollars to
Bangladesh and Bangladesh's exports of only 70 million dollars to
India. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
