<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Opposition Submits Memorandum on Local Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Nepal's main opposition has
handed over a memorandum to the Election Commission here demanding
the invalidation of the local elections held last Saturday,
sources said.
</P>
<P>
The Nepali Congress (NC) party alleged in the memorandum that
the first phase of the local elections in West Nepal was plagued
by widespread violence, vandalism and abuse of administrative
power by the ruling side.
</P>
<P>
The memorandum, signed by NC President Girija Prasad Koirala,
urged the commission to declare the Saturday polls null and void
and hold re-elections across West Nepal.
</P>
<P>
A delegation of senior NC leaders Tuesday presented the
memorandum to the commission under a decision by the party
leadership at an earlier meeting, party sources said.
</P>
<P>
The NC memorandum accused the government of failing to secure
law and order during the elections by tacitly encouraging workers
of a major ruling partner to carry out illegal activities against
NC candidates.
</P>
<P>
The workers of the Communist Party of Nepal (United Marxist
Leninist, CPN-UML) prevented NC candidates from filing
nominations, forced them to withdraw nominations and assaulted
ordinary voters, the memorandum claimed.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary results of the local polls indicated that the NC
party, which held the most of the country's local governments
before the elections, was losing its majority control of local
authorities to the CPN-UML, the biggest party in the three-party
ruling coalition under Prime Minister Lokendra Bahadur Chand, who
is from a small party.
</P>
<P>
The Election Commission is unlikely to yield to the NC party's
demand as it has already arranged re-elections in some areas where
the earlier polls were disturbed by clashes between workers of
different political parties, analysts here said.
</P>
<P>
The second phase of local elections, to be held in Central and
East Nepal, is scheduled for May 26.  
</P>
</TEXT>
