<HEADLINE> Netherlands Wants to Sell Submarines to Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The Netherlands has offered to
sell submarines to Malaysia, according to the Malaysian national
news agency Bernama today.
</P>
<P>
The Netherlands is offering a package that includes technology
transfer and training and also assistance to set up a submarine
branch for the Royal Malaysian Navy (RMN), Bernama said, quoting
Dutch Deputy Defense Minister Jan Gmelich Meijling.
</P>
<P>
Meijling, who visited Malaysia recently to promote Dutch
defense-related equipment particularly submarines, said in an
interview with Bernama "talks have been going on for quite some
time."
</P>
<P>
RMN chief Ahmad Ramli Mohamed Noor also visited the Netherlands
to study the offer, he said.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Defense Minister Syed Hamid Albar said earlier his
ministry was looking into the various types of submarines while
awaiting the government's approval to procure its first ever
submarine either new or second hand.
</P>
<P>
So far half a dozen countries such as Sweden, Britain, Germany
and France, have been eyeing to sell submarines to Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
The Netherlands is among the countries to which the RMN sent
its personnel for specialized training in submarine operations and
maintenance. The others are Germany, France, Italy, Britain,
Turkey and France.
</P>
<P>
The Dutch deputy minister said that on a broader perspective,
the Dutch defense industry was willing to work and set up joint
ventures to manufacture defense-related products with Malaysian
companies.
</P>
<P>
He described the existing defense ties between his country and
Malaysia as good and said that several Dutch defense companies are
expected to sign agreement with their Malaysian partners soon or
in the near future.  
</P>
</TEXT>
