<HEADLINE> Nepal Urged to Grace More Time for Qomolangma Climbing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali government has been
asked to allow a grace period for the spring climbing season to
some foreign expeditions, which are being stranded on the south
face of the 8,848-meter Mt. Qomolangma due to bad weather, reports
here said today.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the foreign climbing teams have sent a fax message
to the Nepal Mountaineering Association (NMA) here from the base
camp, asking the NMA to Plead with the government on their behalf
for few more days, according to the association sources.
</P>
<P>
Under Nepal's mountaineering regulations, all climbing teams
have to conclude their expeditions on Himalayan mountains by May
31 when the current spring season ends, otherwise they could be
subject to heavy fines.
</P>
<P>
Six foreign teams, including each from Malaysia, the United
States, Canada, and New Zealand and two from Britain, are
currently attempting to scale the world highest mountain after
paying a royalty of 10,000 U.S. dollars for each member to the
Tourism Ministry, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
An official of the ministry said these stranded climbing teams
could renew their permissions and extend them to the summer season
which subsequently begins on June 1, but ruled out the possibility
to allow spring teams to climb during the summer.
</P>
<P>
Weather forecast for the coming week still brought bad news for
the climbers waiting on high-altitude camps for last opportunities
to make their assaults to the summit.
</P>
<P>
This spring's unusual bad weather conditions including heavy
snow and strong wind in the Mt. Qomolangma area has so far claimed
life of five climbers on the north face in China side. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
