<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Reports 33 New Cases of HIV Infection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Singapore reported 33 new cases
of HIV, the virus that causes AIDS, in the first quarter of this
year and a baby is among the 33 infected Singaporeans, the Straits
Times said today.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time since 1991 that a baby has contracted
HIV through its mother, the newspaper report said, adding that a
baby can get infected while still in the womb, but most infections
occur during the birth process itself.
</P>
<P>
Quoting figures from the Ministry of Health, the report said
that all but two of the cases were infected through sexual
intercourse. Apart from the infant who was infected by its mother,
the other non-sexual case was an intravenous drug user.
</P>
<P>
The ministry reportedly noted that since the first HIV case was
detected in March 1985, the number of new cases reported has
increased each year, from two in 1985 to 139 in 1996, and 33 in
just the first three months of this year.
</P>
<P>
Heterosexual contact is still the main mode of transmission,
affecting 82 percent of the cases. Two were homosexual, and a
further two were bisexual.
</P>
<P>
As of March 31 this year, a total of 591 Singaporeans have been
found to be HIV infected. More than half displayed no symptoms,
while 110 had full-blown AIDS, the Ministry's figures showed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970521.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
