<HEADLINE> Indonesian Police Arrest 20 People Following Jakarta </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Twenty people were arrested Tuesday
for involvement in a riot in Buncit Raya, Mampang Prapatan, South
Jakarta, capital of Indonesia, police said here today.
</P>
<P>
"Those arrested are individuals who committed destructive acts
to public facilities and threw stones," Jakarta police commander
Hamami Nata said.
</P>
<P>
As the 27-day election campaign period were scheduled to end on
Friday (May 23), thousands of supporters of the United Development
Party (PPP) took to the streets once again on Tuesday despite
party leaders' explicit orders that all rallying activities in the
capital were to be canceled.
</P>
<P>
During the rallies, they lit bonfires and clashed with backers
of the ruling party Golkar in several areas around Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
A mob set a police patrol car on fire in East Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
Police, forced to break up the street battle, took action by
firing tear gas canisters and rubber bullets and by spraying water
from armored vehicles.
</P>
<P>
"Nobody was killed during the rioting," Hamami said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a senior police officer Tuesday denied allegations
that the situation in Jakarta is not safe after a series of riots
erupted in the past few days.
</P>
<P>
"Rumors that the situation is not safe are not true. Security
officers have been making all-out efforts," chief of the
Indonesian police information service Nurfaizi said.
</P>
<P>
He said security officers would take action against supporters
of political parties who insisted on staging motorcades.
</P>
<P>
Nurfaizi said three security officers had been killed while
carrying out their task during the campaign period which began on
April 27.
</P>
<P>
Until Monday, he added, 80 people were killed, mostly in
campaign-related traffic accidents.
</P>
<P>
In this year's campaign, the country is divided into three
groups of campaign areas where the three parties -- the PPP,
Golkar and the Indonesian Democratic Party (PDI) -- could do their
campaign activities in turn.  
</P>
