<DOCNO> XIE19970521.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Urged to Pay For 60 Years of "Genocide" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Australia is bound by
international law to pay compensation for the "genocidal" removal
of as many as 100,000 Aboriginal children from their parents
between 1910 and 1970, an official inquiry has found.
</P>
<P>
The Human Rights and Equal Opportunity Commission (HREOC) under
the federal government also recommends reparations be made to the
affected families and communities and calls for an apology by all
Australian parliaments and police force, the leading newspaper The
Australian reported today.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister John Howard has ruled out financial compensation
and the government's attitude has been that there is no need to
dwell on the past, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The 689-page report, ordered by the former federal government,
concludes that the policies of forced removal constituted a "crime
against humanity" which amounted to genocide, the newspaper said
in a frontage report.
</P>
<P>
"Systematic racial discrimination and genocide must not be
trivialized and Australia's obligation under international law to
make reparations must not be ignored," said the official report
completed last month.
</P>
<P>
In a separate report, the newspaper said Lois O'Donoghue,
former head of a governmental organization in charge of Aboriginal
affairs, was taken from her mother at two.
</P>
<P>
She said "it's very disappointing because the situation that
happened to me and others at that time is not only that we were
removed from our family, but we were denied our culture, our land
and our language, and that's something we have great difficulty
getting back."
</P>
<P>
The report explodes the myth that Aboriginal children were
taken from their families for their welfare during 1910-1970 as
part of the infamous Aboriginal assimilation policies.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald said today that "in fact, the
children, especially young girls, were exploited as cheap labor,
with some as young as 12 being raped by their white foster
fathers, church leaders and the employees of public institution."
</P>
<P>
A nationwide survey conducted in 1994 shows that most families
have been affected, in one or more generations, by the forced
removal of one or more children, and nationally between one in
three and one in 10 Aboriginal children were forcibly removed from
their families and communities during 1910-1970.
</P>
<P>
The report also recommends a national compensation fund and a
national "sorry day" each year to commemorate the history of
forcible removal of children and moves towards giving indigenous
people self-determination over issues such as welfare and justice.
</P>
<P>
The federal government promised yesterday to table the report
in parliament next week.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for Attorney-General Daryl Williams confirmed the
government had received the report last month but denied that it
was delaying its public release.
</P>
<P>
Indigenous, church and human rights groups yesterday united to
urge the federal government to address the findings.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970521.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Competitiveness Ranking Drops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Thailand has lost four places in
its annual world competitiveness rankings, from 14th to 18th,
according to the Nation Daily today.
</P>
<P>
In the 1997 World Economic Forum (WEF) index, released in
Switzerland on Tuesday, Thailand places 10th in market growth
index and is one of the top recipients of foreign direct
investment.
</P>
<P>
However, Thailand is weak in terms of import barriers, tax
burden and evasion, government competence, technology, labor
productivity and quality of legal institutions.
</P>
<P>
The overall ranking of competitiveness, surveyed among 53
countries and regions in the world, is based on 155 criteria,
drawn from eight key factors, including openness to international
trade and finance; role of the government budget and regulation;
development of financial markets; quality of infrastructure,
technology and business management; labor market flexibility, and
quality of judicial and political institutions.
</P>
<P>
Thailand is among countries in which government policies
worsened in the past year, according to the WEF index.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
