<HEADLINE> Russian Newspapers Flood Ukrainian Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, May 20 (Xinhua) -- Russian newspapers and magazines are
nearly eight times more popular in Ukraine than Ukrainian
publications and the parliament is getting worried.
</P>
<P>
The number and circulation of Russian publications has soared
since the government scrapped a law which allowed only three
Moscow-based newspapers to be sold on Ukrainian news stands.
</P>
<P>
Now, 155 of the 267 newspapers on sale in Ukraine are either in
Russian or are bilingual and Ukrainian publications are getting
squeezed out.
</P>
<P>
The country's parliament is currently debating a bill to
regulate the languages used by the media. The move comes in the
wake of a decision by the government late last year to set up an
Information Ministry to help Ukrainian language publications.
</P>
<P>
Surveys show that 54 Russian newspapers and magazines are
sold for every 100 Ukrainians, compared with just seven Ukrainian
publications.
</P>
<P>
Although Ukrainian was made the only official language in
Ukraine following independence from the former Soviet Union in
1991, one in five of the country's 51 million people is ethnic
Russian and many native Ukrainians prefer speaking Russian.
</P>
<P>
Even children born after independence are more fluent in
Russian than Ukrainian. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970521.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
