<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Applications to Thai Investment Board Falls 22 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Net applications for direct
investment submitted by Thai and foreign investors to the Board of
Investment (BOI) of Thailand fell by 22.3 percent in the first
quarter of the year from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The sharp drop came amid a decline in Thailand's macro-economic
stability, which is being threatened by problems in the finance
and property sectors.
</P>
<P>
Other factors included the lower yen, which made Japanese
products cheaper at home, according to BOI.
</P>
<P>
Net investment applications submitted to BOI during
January-March of 1997 totaled 153.9 billion baht (6.16 billion US
dollars), a decrease of over 22 percent compared to the same
period of 1996, which had 197.4 billion baht (7.9 billion dollar)
worth of investment, according to BOI.
</P>
<P>
Investment projects applied through BOI usually enjoy
promotional privileges, such as import duty reductions and tax
holidays.
</P>
<P>
Investments sought by Taiwanese businesses had the sharpest
drop, with only 20 projects worth 400 million baht (16 million
dollars) in equity investments applied for in the first three
months of 1997, compared to 8.7 billion baht (348 million dollars)
for 20 projects in the first quarter of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Japanese and American projects also dropped to 4 billion baht
(160 million dollars) and 7.1 billion baht (284 million dollars)
from 6.3 billion baht (252 million dollars) and 10.9 billion baht
(436 million dollars) respectively.
</P>
<P>
However, European investors applied for more investments with 2
billion baht (80 million dollars) worth of equity investment
projects, compared to only 300 million baht (12 million dollars)
in the first quarter of last year.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong, the fifth largest investor in the country, applied
for projects worth 100 million baht (4 million dollars) during the
first quarter.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
