<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia's Economy Expects Slight Increase This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 20 (Xinhua) -- Russia's economy is moving toward
stability as the gross domestic product is expected to grow 2
percent in 1997 or stay the same as last year, a senior official
at the Ministry of Economy said today.
</P>
<P>
Figures of the ministry showed that imports fell 4 percent and
exports rose 3 percent between January and April this year,
compared with the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The actual income of citizens increased 4 percent, and the
production of raw materials, chemistry and machinery remained
stable.
</P>
<P>
Residents whose average monthly income was lower than the
subsistence level of 400,000 rubble (about 70 U.S. dollars)
accounted for 21 percent of the total population in the first four
months this year, down 3 percent from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The gap between the rich and poor is widening as the richest
people, making up for about 10 percent of the country's total
population, have aggregated 32.3 percent of Russia's wealth.
</P>
<P>
The Russian government has outlined seven priority targets for
the near future, of which top consideration will be given to
helping the poor and revitalizing Russia's national industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
