<DOCNO> XIE19970521.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Bronzes Found </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archaeologists have recently
proved that people in Hubei Province in the central part of China
were able to produce high-quality bronze at least 2,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The evidence comes in the form of smelted ore that is 94
percent bronze and a residue that contained less than 0.7 percent
bronze, which was found at the Tonglushan Smelter Site in Hubei's
Daye city, which was discovered in 1973.
</P>
<P>
The smelter was built in the Western Zhou Dynasty (11th c.BC
- 771 BC). It operated for more than 1,000 years until the Western
Han Dynasty (206 BC-24 AD) when it witnessed the transition from
the Bronze to the Iron age. It is the largest and best preserved
ancient bronze smelter in the world.
</P>
<P>
The ancient Chinese smelted ore at some 1,200 degrees Celsius,
while their Egyptian counterparts could only smelt and cast metals
at lower temperatures at that time, experts say.
</P>
<P>
Also found at the two-sq-km site were hundreds of wells, some
30-60 m deep, more than 100 horizontal channels for pouring, three
smelting workshops with eight furnaces, and a great number of
tools made of bronze, iron, wood, bamboo, stone, and bone, as well
as pottery for daily use.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970521.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
