<HEADLINE> Annan Calls on Germany, Britain to Stay in UNIDO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, May 20 (Xinhua) -- United Nations Secretary-General
Kofi Annan today called on Germany and Britain not to withdraw
from the United Nations Industrial Development Organization
(UNIDO).
</P>
<P>
Annan, in a speech to U.N. staff working in Vienna,
urged that Germany and Britain should support the UNIDO, set up in
1967 to bolster industrial development in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Following the United States and Canada's withdrawal from the
UNIDO, Britain, Australia and Germany also said they would follow
suit at the end of this year, accusing the organization of failing
to carry out needed reforms.
</P>
<P>
Annan stressed that wide-range reforms would be carried out to
improve the efficiency of U.N. organizations, including the
UNIDO. He asked Germany and Britain, which are among the largest
contributors to the UNIDO, to support the reforms.
</P>
<P>
He said he would suggest that the international anti-terrorism
troops be permanently stationed in Vienna.
</P>
<P>
He praised the U.N. office in Vienna, the International Atomic
Energy Agency (IAEA) and the UNIDO, both based in Vienna, for
cooperating well in their work.
</P>
<P>
Annan also praised high-ranking women officials working for the
U.N. at its Vienna agencies, saying they are playing an
increasingly important role there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
