<HEADLINE> Northeast China Mountains Rich In Economic Plants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Changchun, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The Changbai Mountains in northeast
China's Jilin Province are expected to play a bigger role in
promoting local economic development, as they have been found rich
in wild plants.
</P>
<P>
A two-year scientific survey that ended recently showed that
there are in the mountains 2,077 varieties of wild plants,
including 1,600 of economic value.
</P>
<P>
And 875 kinds of them are medical plants, like ginseng,
dangshen (Codonopsis pilosula), tuber of elevated gastrodia
(Gastrodia elata). One of China's three medicinal material
production bases lies in these mountains.
</P>
<P>
The mountains rank fourth in forest resources and second in
annual wood production in China. There have been more than 280
species of nectariferous plants in the mountains, and the linden
honey products have won wide reputation.
</P>
<P>
The mountains also boast of edible wild vegetables, aromatic
plants, fiber plants, ornamental plants, and plants that contain
rich vitamins, sugars, amino acids, and minerals.
</P>
<P>
Local people have turned the mountains into one of China's
major forest zones and important bee-raising bases.
</P>
<P>
Some of the economic plant resources have been destroyed due to
random exploitation. Local governments are taking effective
measures to maintain ecologically sustainable development.
</P>
</TEXT>
