<HEADLINE> American Countries Review Summit of Americas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, May 20 (Xinhua) -- Officials from 34 American
countries gathered here today to review the First Summit of the
Americas.
</P>
<P>
During the two-day meeting, chaired by acting Uruguayan Foreign
Minister Carlos Perez del Castillo at the ocean resort of Punta
del Este, 130 kilometers east of Montevideo, participants would
review the implementation of decisions taken at the first Summit
of the Americas held in December 1994 in Miami, the United States.
</P>
<P>
They are also expected to discuss the agenda of the Second
Summit of the Americas to be held in Santiago, Chile, in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Perez del Castillo put forward at the meeting his government's
proposal that the agenda of the next summit should be concentrated
on four or five topics so as to ensure thorough studies.
</P>
<P>
During the first summit, the 34 heads of governments of the
Americas signed a declaration of principles and a plan of
actions. The two documents touched some 100 issues ranging from
trade liberalization to environmental protection, from advancement
of democracy to anti-corruption measures, and from education to
health care.
</P>
<P>
The leaders also agreed to finish negotiations on establishing
the Free Trade Area of the Americas before 2005.
</P>
<P>
Also attending today's meeting are representatives of the
Organization of American States, the Inter-American Development
Bank, the U.N. Economic Commission for Latin America and the
Pan-American Health Organization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
