<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Security Council to Expand to 20-26 Member States: Annan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, May 20 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
said today he hoped the U.N. Security Council would be
expanded from the present 15 members to between 20 and 26 member
states.
</P>
<P>
He was speaking after talks with Austrian President Thomas
Klestil, Chancellor Viktor Klima, Vice-Chancellor and Foreign
Minister Wolfgang Schussel and President of the National Council
Heinz Fischer.
</P>
<P>
Their talks mainly centered on U.N. reforms, Austria's role in
the United Nations and the situation in some of the world's hot
spots.
</P>
<P>
Annan said the Security Council needed to be enlarged to
20 to 26 members to "go along with the present world political
reality."
</P>
<P>
The council now has 15 members with five permanent seats and
10 seats which rotate every two years among other U.N. members.
</P>
<P>
A U.N. working group is currently discussing the enlargement
issue. Japan and Germany have both been lobbying for a permanent
seat on the council. But developing countries want more members
on the council because they fear they won't be fairly represented.
</P>
<P>
Industrial nations, Annan noted, wanted membership increased to 20
whereas developing countries wanted a much bigger Security
Council. The final decision will be made by all U.N. members.
</P>
<P>
At the press conference, Annan thanked Austria for its active
participation in U.N. work and peace-keeping missions.
</P>
<P>
Annan also met with Franz Vranitzky, the commissioner for
Albania with the Organization of Security and Cooperation in
Europe (OSCE), and discussed the situation in the country which is
preparing for elections after being shaken by unrest in February
and March. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
