<HEADLINE> China's Northeast Helping Unemployed Workers Get New Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, May 21 (Xinhua) -- About a million laid-off workers
in northeast China's province of Liaoning have found new jobs with
the help of local governments and grass-roots organizations,
according to official sources here.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning is China's oldest heavy industry base and has one-tenth
of the country's state-owned enterprises, but many have long been
plagued by poor economic performance and overstaffing.
</P>
<P>
Over the past several years, state-owned enterprises laid
off more workers as the country moves ahead with its reforms and
improves efficiency. Liaoning is believed to have the most
unemployed workers in the country with 1.6 million, according to
local sources.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government has placed equal emphasis on grain
production, a "vegetable basket" project, and re-employment, with
the hope of putting people back to work.
</P>
<P>
Local governments have also been helpful, developing 140
preferential policies to help people find jobs, while social
organizations have also done a lot of work in helping them find
new jobs.
</P>
<P>
Trade unions helped establish 203 job markets and more than
3,000 agencies in 1996, where 16,000 people found new jobs, and
local industrial and commercial departments have helped 150,000
people employed over the past two years.
</P>
<P>
The province has set up 1,400 job agencies, and financial
departments have started services to insure workers against
unemployment.
</P>
<P>
Seven million workers at local state-owned enterprises,
collectively-owned businesses, and overseas-backed ventures have
taken out unemployment insurance. In the past three years, while
the province has been implementing the re-employment scheme,
financial organizations at various levels have given 340 million
yuan to help the unemployed get through their difficulties.
</P>
<P>
The province will continue to build more job agencies and
expand labor exports to help people find work in other areas, said
Dai Mingshun, chief of the Liaoning Provincial Bureau of
Labor. They have set a goal of helping one million more find
employment by the year 2000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
