<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, May 20 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries over the past
few days:
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- A total of 161,000 jobs were created during the
1987-1996 period in Uruguay, with an annual growth rate of 1.2
percent, said the National Institute of Statistics in Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- Sixty-five percent of the rural population in El
Salvador live in poverty, according to a report by the Salvadoran
Foundation for Economic and Social Development.
</P>
<P>
Two million farmers live in poverty and 19 percent of them live
in abject poverty, because about 31 percent of arable lands are
eroded. El Salvador had an overall economic growth of 6.7 percent
between 1991 and 1995, but agricultural growth was only 2.5
percent during the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazil's National Steel Company, the biggest in the
country, will invest about 47 million dollars over the next five
years in the development of new technology to increase steel
production.
</P>
<P>
The company produces 4.2 million tons of steel every year and
expects to rise to 5.1 million tons by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Exports of salmon earned 228.2 million dollars
during the first quarter of this year, an increase of 43.6 percent
over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
According to figures provided by the Salmon and Trout Farmers
Association, 53.4 million tons of salmon were shipped to Japan,
the United States and Brazil during the first quarter of this
year, an increase of 18.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- Tax collections in Costa Rica increased 22.6 during
the first four months of this year, compared with the same period
in 1996, according to the Finance Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Income tax revenues increased 20 percent over the same period
in 1996, sales tax revenues 48 percent and customs duties 28
percent.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- In 1996 Mexico produced 49,178 tons of honey,
with 80 percent of them earmarked for export and the rest for
domestic consumption.
</P>
<P>
Mexico is the fourth largest honey-producing country in the
world after China, the United States and Argentina and the third
largest exporter after China and Argentina. The production is the
second largest source of hard currency in the subsector of
livestock with earnings of 46.8 million dollars per year.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Uruguayan rice exports reached the unprecedented
volume of 642,000 tons in 1996 and revenues of 228.5 million
dollars, said the Association of Rice Growers.
</P>
<P>
Brazil is the most important importer of Uruguayan rice, with
more than 476,000 tons at a cost of 166 million dollars which
accounts for 73 percent of Uruguay's rice exports.
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- The consumption of electrical energy in Venezuela
increased 3.9 percent in 1996, according to the Venezuelan
Electrical Industry Chamber.
</P>
<P>
The industrial sector had the biggest increase in consumption
with 49 percent, followed by private homes with 22 percent, the
public sector with 16 percent and commerce 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
Higher consumption was also accompanied by changes in power
generation which increased 2.87 percent compared with 1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
