<HEADLINE> Renovated Imperial Mausoleum Opens to Public </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The mausoleum for the fourth
emperor of the Northern Song Dynasty (960-1127), which has been in
renovation since 1995, opens to the public in central China's
Henan Province.
</P>
<P>
All buildings set up in the mausoleum against regulations
concerning cultural relics protection have been dismantled;
Song-style pavilions, gates and pass leading to the tomb have been
rebuilt.
</P>
<P>
The renovation project, expected to be completed by the end of
this century, has drawn an investment of 120 million yuan. So far
45 million yuan has been used.
</P>
<P>
The mausoleum, Yongzhaoling, was built for Zhao Zhen, or
Emperor Renzong who ruled the country for 42 years. It is one of
the largest of eight imperial tombs in the Songling, the Song imperial
tombs.
</P>
<P>
Songling, covering an area of 37 sq km, is famous for its
unique stone carvings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
