<HEADLINE> 1997 Global Competitiveness Rankings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The Geneva-based World Economic
Forum (WEF) today released its Global Competitiveness Report
covering a total of 53 countries and regions all over the world.
</P>
<P>
The rankings are based on 155 criteria with eight major factors
determining competitiveness: openness of an economy to
international trade and finance, role of the government budget and
regulation, development of financial markets, quality of
infrastructure, quality of technology, quality of business
management, labor market flexibility, and quality of judicial and
political institution.
</P>
<P>
The following are 1997 global competitiveness rankings with
1996 rankings in brackets:
</P>
<P>
Singapore (1), Hong Kong (2), the United States (4), Canada
(8), New Zealand (3), Switzerland (6), The United Kingdom (15),
Taiwan (9), Malaysia (10), Norway (7), Luxembourg (5), the
Netherlands (17), Chile (18), Japan (13), Indonesia (30), Ireland
(26), Australia (12), Thailand (14), Finland (16), Denmark (11),
South Korea (20), Sweden (21), France (23), Israel (24), Germany
(22), Spain (32), Austria (19), Egypt (29), China (36), Portugal
(34), Belgium (25), the Czech Republic (35), Mexico (33), the
Philippines (31), the Slovak Republic (N/A), Turkey (42),
