<HEADLINE> Cuba to Increase Rice Production In 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, May 20 (Xinhua) -- Cuba will produce 200,000 tons of
rice this year, 55,000 tons over 1996, Cuban Agriculture Minister
Jordan Morales said in an interview published by the local press
today.
</P>
<P>
The rice harvested between March 1996 and March 1997 yielded
145,000 tons, 25,000 tons over the 1995-1996 season when
production levels of this cereal began to recover, Morales was
quoted as saying by the "Business in Cuba" weekly magazine.
</P>
<P>
Efforts are now made to increase efficiency, reduce production
costs and increase yields congruent with the financial resources
used for the production of rice, he added.
</P>
<P>
The minister pointed out that rice plantations have been
overhauled over the past year with financing from European and
Chinese banks to raise production from 3.5 tons/hectare to 5.0
tons/hectare.
</P>
<P>
Cubans consume about 500,000 tons of rice per year and the
government has to spend about 90 million U.S. dollars to make up
the shortfall of rice each year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
