<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Background: ABCs of Basic Law of Hong Kong SAR (95-96) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 21 (Xinhua) -- Following are the ABCs of the Basic
Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (95-96) in a
question-and-answer format:
</P>
<P>
Question: Under what circumstances may representatives of the
government of the Hong Kong SAR participate in diplomatic
negotiations?
</P>
<P>
Answer: After 1997, representatives of the government of the
Hong Kong SAR may, as members of delegations of the government of
China, participate in all negotiations at the diplomatic level if
such negotiations directly affect the region.
</P>
<P>
The three conditions for the participation in diplomatic
negotiations of representatives of the government of the Hong Kong
SAR are:
</P>
<P>
1) Such negotiations are conducted by the central government of
China;
</P>
<P>
2) Such negotiations directly affect the Hong Kong SAR;
</P>
<P>
3) Representatives of the Hong Kong SAR government do not
participate in such negotiations in an independent capacity but as
members of delegations of the Chinese government.
</P>
<P>
Question: What about Taiwan institutions in Hong Kong after
China resumes the exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong?
</P>
<P>
Answer: Both Taiwan and Hong Kong are inalienable territory of
the People's Republic of China. Exchanges between the inland
areas, Taiwan and Hong Kong in the fields of economy, trade,
culture, science and technology have kept increasing, and their
relations are becoming ever closer.
</P>
<P>
In principle, when Hong Kong returns to the motherland in 1997,
Taiwan's institutions and personnel in Hong Kong will be permitted
to remain. Hong Kong and Taiwan will continue to maintain and
develop economic, cultural and transportation ties.
</P>
<P>
But Taiwan will not be allowed to have official organizations
in Hong Kong. Taiwan organizations in Hong Kong must abide by some
basic principles.
</P>
<P>
For example, they must not engage in activities that aim to
split China and sabotage the reunification of the motherland such
as advocating "two Chinas" or "one China, one Taiwan;" they must
not engage in any activities that impede the development of
cross-strait relations; they must abide by the Basic Law and
decrees and regulations of the Hong Kong SAR; and they must not
engage in activities that impair the stability and prosperity of
the Hong Kong SAR. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970521.0283 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia, Japan Resume Full Diplomatic Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, May 20 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslavia and Japan resumed
full diplomatic relations today when they agreed to exchange
ambassadors, the Tanjug news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Top level diplomatic contact was suspended after sanctions were
imposed on Yugoslavia by the United Nations during the nearly
four-year war in the country.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also reconfirmed the effectiveness of
previous agreements made between them and international accords.
</P>
<P>
The full normalization of ties has provided the two countries
with wide-ranging possibilities for cooperation, particularly
economic cooperation, the agency said.  
</P>
