<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Stands 29th in 1997 Global Competitiveness Ranking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, May 21 (Xinhua) -- China has moved from the 36th place
in 1996 to the 29th in the 1997 Global Competitiveness Ranking,
said the Global Competitiveness Report released today by the
Geneva-based World Economic Forum (WEF).
</P>
<P>
The rankings of a total of 53 countries and regions in the
world are based on 155 criteria with eight major factors
determining competitiveness: openness of an economy to
international trade and finance, role of the government budget and
regulation, development of financial markets, quality of
infrastructure, technology and business management, labor market
flexibility, and quality of judicial and political institutions.
</P>
<P>
The WEF says in its report that China's leap forward is mainly
due to the country's economic reforms in labor market and tax
policies.
</P>
<P>
In an opinion survey of some 3,000 business leaders worldwide
based mainly on their subjective judgements, China places ninth in
the competitiveness rankings.
</P>
<P>
In another ranking based on the market growth index, China, the
world's fastest growing economy, ranks second only behind the
United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
