<DOCNO> XIE19970521.0290 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WEF Releases 1997 Global Competitiveness Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, May 21 (Xinhua) -- The Geneva-based World Economic
Forum (WEF) today released its Global Competitiveness Report
covering a total of 53 countries and regions all over the world.
</P>
<P>
The top 10 economies of high competitiveness are Singapore,
Hong Kong, the United States, Canada, New Zealand, Switzerland,
the United Kingdom, Taiwan, Malaysia and Norway.
</P>
<P>
The rankings are based on 155 criteria with eight major factors
determining competitiveness: openness of an economy to
international trade and finance, role of the government budget and
regulation, development of financial markets, quality of
infrastructure, quality of technology, quality of business
management, labor market flexibility and quality of judicial and
political institution.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia, with its ranking rising steeply from last year's
30th place to the 15th this year, has become the most competitive
country among the big emerging markets, the WEF report said.
</P>
<P>
China, the world's fastest growing economy, has moved from the
36th place in 1996 to the 29th due to the country's successful
reforms in labor market and tax policies and its absorption of
foreign direct investment of 42 billion U.S. dollars, it said.
</P>
<P>
Singapore and Hong Kong have kept their leading places in the
competitiveness ranking.
</P>
<P>
Chile continues as Latin America's brightest star, rising from
the 18th place in 1996 to the 13th. Market-friendly economic
policies are believed to have dramatically improved its growth
performance of 6.9 percent, the highest in Latin America, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
The United States emerges as the most competitive among the
large economies with populations of over 10 million. The two key
areas determining long-term productivity growth in advanced
nations - technology and management - have played a decisive role
in raising the country from last year's fourth place to the third.
</P>
<P>
Other factors include its labor market flexibility,
technological prowess and low fiscal deficit of 1.4 percent in
1996, which represented the industrial world's lowest.
</P>
<P>
Canada has moved from last year's eighth place to the fourth
thanks to its success in curbing fiscal deficit.
</P>
<P>
Among the European countries, the United Kingdom has jumped
from the 15th place in 1996 to this year's seventh, with the
Netherlands from the 17th to the 12th, Ireland from the 26th to
the 16th and Norway keeping a place in the top 10 from last
year's 7th.
</P>
<P>
Russia has slid to the bottom of the global competitiveness
ranking of the 53 countries and regions from last year's 49th.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
