<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Irrigation Network Found in Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, May 21 (Xinhua) -- A well-preserved irrigation network
dug in the Han Dynasty (206 BC-220 AD) has been found in northwest
China's Gansu Province.
</P>
<P>
Over 200 km of canals and ditches were found existing in Anxi
county. The ditches measured one meter wide and one meter deep.
</P>
<P>
For more than a thousand years, the network introduced water
from a river some 50 km away and irrigated an area of over 30,000
hectares in present-day wasteland.
</P>
<P>
Also found in the area were remains of a city and military
facilities from the Tang Dynasty (618-907), suggesting a
prosperous oasis at that time, Chinese archaeologists say.
</P>
<P>
According to the experts, the site became desertified during
the Yuan Dynasty (1271-1368) when the central government took the
place for military use and relocated all local residents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
