<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Opposing Faction Denies Taliban's Gains in Central </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 21 (Xinhua) -- An opposing faction has denied
the Afghan Islamic militia Taliban's claim that it had captured
the strategic Shibar pass in central Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
A Hezb-i-Wahdat official in northwestern Pakistan's Peshawar
city Tuesday rejected the Taliban claim as an "absolute lie",
stressing that the pass was still under the faction's control, the
Afghan Islamic Press (AIP) reported.
</P>
<P>
Both sides were still locked in a stalemate at frontlines in
central Bamyan province, the official said.
</P>
<P>
The Shibar pass is only five kilometers from Bamyan city, a
stronghold of the Hezb-i-Wahdat allied with northern warlord
Rashid Dostum.
</P>
<P>
"The Taliban launched an offensive early this morning around
Sheikh Ali town, but the frontlines remain in the same position,"
the official was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Ali is situated about 20 kilometers east of the pass and
the rival forces have been locked in a stalemate there since the
Taliban advanced up the valley in January this year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, it is reported that the Taliban, who launched a
major offensive Tuesday, had made key gains in central and
northern Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The northwestern provinces of Badghis, Faryab and Sar-e-Pol
fell into Taliban hands after the defection of Dostum's right-hand
man, Abdul Malik, reports from Kabul said.
</P>
<P>
The reports said following Malik's revolt, most parts of the
northeastern province of Kunduz and Baghlan have also been
captured and heavy fighting was still going on around
Mazar-e-Sharif, Dostum's headquarters, about 300 kilometers from
Kabul.  
</P>
</TEXT>
