<HEADLINE> UNGA Elects 11 Judges to Int'l Tribunal for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 20 (Xinhua) -- The UN General Assembly
today elected the 11 judges to the International Criminal Tribunal
for the former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The newly elected judges to the tribunal are Antonio Cassese of
Italy, Richard George May of the United Kingdom, Mohamed
Shabuddeen of Guyana, Wang Tieya of China, Claude Jorda of France,
Gabrielle Kirk McDonald of the United States, Fouad Abdel-Moneim
Riad of Egypt; Lal Chand Vohrah of Malaysia, Rafael Nieto Navia of
Columbia, Florence Ndepele Mwachende Mumba of Zambia and Almiro
Simoes Rodrigues of Portual.
</P>
<P>
They will serve four-year term starting from November 17 this
year.
</P>
<P>
The international tribunal for the former Yugoslavia was
established according to Security Council resolution 827 (1993).
The first 11 judges were elected by the General Assembly in
September 1993 for a term of four years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
