<DOCNO> XIE19970521.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. to Expand Crackdown on Medicare Fraud </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 20 (Xinhua) -- Success of a two-year crackdown
on Medicare fraud in five states prompted the U.S. Government to
expand it to a dozen more states Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"This is a model that works. Now it's time to take what we've
learned and use it broadly and aggressively," said Donna Shalala,
the Health and Human Services secretary.
</P>
<P>
Medicare is the federal health insurance program covering more
than 37 million elderly and disabled Americans.
</P>
<P>
The anti-fraud campaign, started in 1995 and known as
"Operation Restore Trust," will eventually cover all 50 states,
Shalala said.
</P>
<P>
Over the next two years, it will expand to a dozen more states.
</P>
<P>
During its initial phase, federal investigators targeted fraud
by home health agencies, nursing homes, medical equipment
suppliers and hospices, in California, Florida, New York, Texas,
and Illinois.
</P>
<P>
Shalala said, 74 criminal convictions have recovered 67.3
million dollars for Medicare, 58 civil cases have brought in
another 72.8 million dollars in fines and settlements, and
companies have returned 47.4 million dollars for services
inappropriately provided or billed.
</P>
<P>
Medicare has shut out 218 fraudulent health care providers, and
investigators still are working on 210 cases.
</P>
<P>
Medicare administrator Bruce Vladeck said cooperation between
Medicare and state Medicaid offices also helped identify cases in
which both the federal health program for the aging and state
programs for the poor and disabled were billed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970521.0307 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Imposes Sanctions on Burma </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 20 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton, citing
so-called human rights abuses, announced on Tuesday to impose
sanctions on Burma, which includes a ban on U.S. investment in its
oil and natural gas development.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, who announced in April that he intended to impose the
sanctions, said in a letter to Congress that he was taking the
action because of "serious abuses" by the State Law and Order
Restoration Council in Burma against opponents.
</P>
<P>
The order prohibits U.S. citizens from entering into contracts
that involve the economic development of resources in Burma.
</P>
<P>
It also prohibits Americans from purchasing ownership shares in
developing resources in the country or helping non-U.S. citizens
who wish to perform activities forbidden under the ban.
</P>
<P>
Roger Beach, the chairman of the oil and gas company Unocal
Cop. -- the largest U.S. investor in Burma -- said he was
disappointed with the decision to impose sanctions because it
would hurt economic development.
</P>
<P>
The United States is the fourth largest investor in Burma,
after France, Singapore and Thailand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
