<HEADLINE> New York Stocks Rebound </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 20 (Xinhua) -- Stocks on Wall Street rallied
today, led by technology shares and financial services issues,
after Federal Reserve decided to leave interest rates intact.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average gained 74.58 points, or about
1 percent, to 7,303.46, about 30 points shy of its all-time high
set last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The gauge of 30 big companies had fallen by as much as 76
points before today's Fed policy meeting ended without any change
in the central bank's interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 4-to-3 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange. Its volume increased to 447.17
million shares from the 345.14 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list rose 8.39 to 841.66, and
the NYSE's composite index rose 3.06 to 437.20, leaving both
measures less than a point shy of record territory.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index rose 22.34, or 1.7 percent, to
1,363.58, moving within 25 points of its all-time high, set back
in January.
</P>
<P>
The American Stock Exchange composite index rose 3.28 to
590.76.
</P>
<P>
Among leading Nasdaq technology issues, Intel, Dell Computer,
Cisco Systems and Microsoft posted big gains.
</P>
<P>
IBM, meanwhile, jumped the equivalent of 19 Dow points to lead
the blue-chip average.
</P>
<P>
Trading had been extremely hesitant in advance of today's Fed
meeting. 
</P>
