<HEADLINE> Kofi Annan Stresses Poverty Eradication </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 20 (Xinhua) -- Poverty is a challenge that
no country, developed or developing, can afford to ignore and is a
top priority goal of the United Nations agenda, UN
Secretary-General Kofi Annan said today.
</P>
<P>
In a message to the annual session of the special event on
poverty eradication held by the United Nations Development Program
(UNDP) and the United Nations Population Fund (UNFPA), he noted
that some 1.3 billion people in the world currently live in
absolute poverty, with incomes of less than a dollar a day.
</P>
<P>
"Poverty is growing as fast as populations. In Sub-Saharan
Africa, it is estimated that half of the people will be living in
absolute poverty by the year 2000," he said.
</P>
<P>
Annan said that UN can become a powerful force for development
-- for development targeted at poverty eradication, in the
following aspects: as a democratic voice of the weak; as a forum
of consensus-based action; through its advocacy and outreach role;
by forging new alliances and partnerships; through balancing
private interests and the public good; through the promotion of
share values; and through cost-effective and efficient development
activities.
</P>
<P>
The major themes of the programs of action of the United
Nations conferences in the 1990s together provide the basis for
comprehensive action against poverty and for the improvement of
the quality of life of the whole population, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
