<HEADLINE> Dollar Falls After Fed Leaves Interest Rates Unchanged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 20 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar sank against most
other major currencies Tuesday after the Federal Reserve left U.S.
interest rates unchanged, an act disappointing to traders.
</P>
<P>
Many traders expected the Fed's policy-making committee to
boost the federal funds rate, an important benchmark, a quarter
percentage point as a pre-emptive strike against inflationary
pressure in the economy.
</P>
<P>
The dollar settled in New York at 113.04 yen, down from 115.68
yen Monday, and at 1.6823 marks, down from 1.7083 marks.
</P>
<P>
The pound cost 1.6570 U.S. dollars, up from 1.6393 U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Japan's official discount rate, the interest rate charged by
the central bank for loans to commercial banks, now stands at a
historic low of 0.5 percent. Despite its low rate since September
1995, Japan's economy has remained sluggish.
</P>
<P>
By mid-afternoon, the dollar plunged after the central bank
announced that it had left the benchmark short-term interest rate
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Monday:
1.3905 Swiss francs, down from 1.4270; 5.6675 French francs, down
from 5.7565; 1,656.00 Italian lire, down from 1,675.00; 1.3664
Canadian dollars, down from 1.3715.  
