<HEADLINE> Canada to Send 15 RCMP Officers to Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, May 20 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Foreign Affairs Minister
Lloyd Axworthy announced here today that Canada is sending 15
Royal Canadian Mounted Police (RCMP) officers to Bosnia to
participate in the United Nations International Police Task Force
(IPTF).
</P>
<P>
The officers are being deployed under the terms of recently
concluded Administrative Arrangement concerning funding for RCMP
participation in international peacekeeping missions.
</P>
<P>
"Canada is committed to participating actively in the efforts
of the international community to restore peace and order in
Bosnia," said Mr.Axworthy, "This decision further reflects
Canada's emphasis on the important role of civilians in
peace-building and in making the transition from conflict to
stability."
</P>
<P>
The IPTF was established by a UN Security Council Resolution in
December 1995, following the Bosnian Peace Agreement, which was
signed in November of that year. Its mandate is to monitor, advise
and otherwise assist the Bosnian police forces to ensure that they
operate in accordance with internationally recognized standards.
</P>
<P>
The IPTF has a current mandate of 18 months and consists of a
multinational force of approximately 1800 officers from 37
countries. 
