<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Official: NATO Changes Pledge When Threats Occur </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 20 (Xinhua) -- The North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) will change its promise to Russia if new
threats occur, U.S. Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott said
here today.
</P>
<P>
Talbott made the remarks in a speech at the Atlantic Council,
as part of a campaign of the Clinton administration to lobby for
the alliance's expansion.
</P>
<P>
NATO has promised Russia that it will not deploy nuclear forces
nor "substantial troops" on the territories of the new members in
the foreseeable future after it expands.
</P>
<P>
Talbott indicated that these pledges are "reassertions of
NATO's own policy" and not "negotiated limits on NATO's freedom of
action."
</P>
<P>
"The alliance reserves the unilateral right to reassess the
security environment at any time, and if it felt there was a new
challenge, to change deployments accordingly," he added.
</P>
<P>
Talbott also reiterated that the membership of the alliance
is open, even to Russia, after NATO decides on the first group
in July in Madrid.
</P>
<P>
He rejected the criticism that any change in NATO, particularly
expansion, will dilute NATO's strength.
</P>
<P>
"Just the opposite is true," he said. "NATO was strong during
the Cold War because it was dynamic and faced the security
challenges as they existed at the time."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said the costs of NATO expansion will be debated
much more than the expansion itself in the Senate. The U.S. will
have to pay 200 million U.S. dollars a year for ten years for the
expansion.
</P>
<P>
Any agreements on accepting new members into NATO will need the
ratification of a two-third majority in the Senate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
