<HEADLINE> U.S. Chamber of Commerce Supports MFN Extension to China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 20 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Chamber of Commerce on
Tuesday welcomed President Bill Clinton's decision to extend the
Most Favored Nation (MFN) trade status to China for the coming
year and pledged to exert its efforts for the approval in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
Willard A. Workman, Chamber vice president, international, said
colleagues were "pleased" that the president did propose a
one-year extension. But he also expressed disappointment for not
asking Congress for a permanent and unconditional extension of
MFN.
</P>
<P>
Workman pointed out that U.S. companies export more than 14
billion US dollars a year in goods and services to China, which
supports more than 200,000 high-wage U.S. jobs in virtually every
state.
</P>
<P>
"Trade with China provides a solid basis for a U.S.-China
dialogue," he said. "All MFN means is the normal trade treatment
now granted all but a handful of countries."
</P>
<P>
Failure to grant China MFN status also would do immense harm
to Hong Kong, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
