<HEADLINE> France to Sell Saudi Arabia a Third Frigate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 20 (Xinhua) -- France announced today that it has
signed a contract with Saudi Arabia on the selling by France to
the kingdom of a third frigate since 1996.
</P>
<P>
French Prime Minister Alain Juppe made the announcement this
evening on TF1 television channel, saying that the contract would
bring about orders worth billions of francs.
</P>
<P>
"Following the voyage that the president of the republic made
last year in Saudi Arabia, we just learned that that country
ordered with us a third `Lafayette' frigate," said Juppe.
</P>
<P>
He said that the deal "would represent billions of (francs) in
orders and 2,600 consolidated jobs for five years."
</P>
<P>
The French presidential office hailed this evening the signing
of the new contract and said that President Jacques Chirac has
personally intervened for winning the contract.
</P>
<P>
The French Defense Ministry said that Saudi Arabia also ordered
three other medium-sized "ultra-modern" navy vessels with
France.
</P>
<P>
Chirac visited Saudi Arabia in July 1996 and signed with Saudi
Arabia the selling of two frigates under a contract named "Sawari
II."
</P>
<P>
According to the French presidential office, France signed a
total of from 95 to 100 billion francs (19-20 billion U.S.
dollars) of contracts with foreign countries, 10 percent of which
were won under "a strong political support" from the government.
</P>
<P>
The announcement on the deal was made five days before the
holding of the first round of France's legislative elections on
May 25. 
</P>
</TEXT>
