<HEADLINE> Wage Rises in UK Make Savings Industry Prosperous </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 20 (Xinhua) -- Rising wages are making the savings
industry in Britain prosperous, with personal saving up by 18
billion pounds (28.8 billion US dollars) in the first quarter of
1997.
</P>
<P>
The inflow of new personal saving was 26 percent higher than in
the first three months of 1996, and 80 percent up in the same
period in 1995, according to Abbey National, the bank.
</P>
<P>
The findings are contained in Abbey National's new savings
index. This combines figures from banks, building societies and
life and unit trust companies.
</P>
<P>
As being a consumer savings industry market for the first time,
it will be the scene of fierce competition this Summer, when
building societies convert to banks, expected financial experts
in the City.
</P>
<P>
Abbey's index shows banks and building societies have won back
a big share of new savings, from a low in mid-1996.
</P>
<P>
At that time they received barely 30 percent of new savings.
That share is now back up to about 60 percent - largely at the
expense of National Savings.
</P>
<P>
National Savings rates look particularly competitive when base
rates are low or falling. But steady National Saving rates look
less attractive than variable bank accounts when base rates are
expected to rise, the City experts said.
</P>
<P>
Barry Naisbitt, chief economist at Abbey National, said that
the first quarter figures could have been distorted by the general
election. But savers were "responding to the political message"
that they would no longer be able to rely on the welfare state in
old age and adversity, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
