<HEADLINE> US Fed Leaves Short-term Interest Rate Unchanged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 20 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Federal Reserve (Fed)
today left the short-term interest rate unchanged, holding the
federal funds rate on overnight loans between banks stable at 5.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. central banks apparently opted to wait and watch for
signs of inflationary pressures before its next policy-making
meeting on July 1-2.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Fed announced today that it had adjourned a meeting of
its policy-setting Federal Open Market Committee (FOMC) and had
nothing further to say.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. economy expanded at a rapid 5.6 percent annual rate in
the first quarter, the best in 10 years, and the unemployment rate
dropped to 4.9 percent in April, the lowest in nearly 24 years.
</P>
<P>
Fearful that strong economic demand would cause accelerating
inflation, the FOMC increased the rate by a quarter percentage
point on March 25, the first increase in two years.
</P>
<P>
But since then there have been signs that the U.S. economic
growth is moderating and the Fed has decided they could wait until
their next meeting to see if the slowdown is pronounced enough to
keep inflation at bay.
</P>
<P>
The rate increase in March drew protests from groups ranging
from the AFL-CIO to the National Association of Manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt and 64 other members of
Congress also criticized the increase in a letter to Fed Chairman
Greenspan. The letter said that "raising interest rate in a
pre-emptive strike against inflation risks damaging our economic
growth" and it was "unwarranted". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
