<HEADLINE> Greenpeace Exposes European Energy Subsidy Negative </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, May 20 (Xinhua) -- Almost 15 billion U.S. dollars in
European taxpayers' money are being spent every year to subsidize
energy systems which damage the climate and increase the nuclear
risk, a Greenpeace report revealed today.
</P>
<P>
The report, Energy Subsidies in Europe, shows that more than 90
percent of direct subsidies from European governments to the
energy industry goes to fossil fuels and nuclear power.
</P>
<P>
This leaves just nine percent of total direct subsidies, or 1.5
billion dollars a year, to clean renewable energy sources, the
report says. In the EU alone, 12 percent goes to renewable energy
and 88 percent is spent on fossil fuels and nuclear energy.
</P>
<P>
Launching the report, which was prepared by the Institute for
Environmental Studies of the Vrije University in Amsterdam,
Greenpeace International climate campaigner Kirsty Hamilton said
the results proved the lie of Europe's environmental rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
"Taxpayers' money is being used to fuel climate change," she
said. "The EU and its member states will not meet current
commitments to cut greenhouse gases by 15 percent by 2010 if they
continue these massive subsidies to the fossil fuel industries."
</P>
<P>
"Greenpeace is calling on Europe to switch subsidies from
fossil fuel and nuclear energy into solar technologies and energy
efficiency."
</P>
<P>
Hamilton said that with less than 650 million dollars the EU
and its member states could install the equivalent of one million
solar homes by 2010 which industry sources say would create 58,000
jobs and save two million tons of carbon dioxide emissions a
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970521.0326 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Ministers Optimistic about Revising EU Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Hague, May 20 (Xinhua) -- European Union foreign ministers
said on Tuesday that they were more optimistic of agreeing the
revision of the EU Treaty at the bloc's Amsterdam summit in
mid-June after narrowing their differences on several key issues.
</P>
<P>
"There are fewer problems and we have shed more light on
others, so they are more suitable for treatment," Dutch Foreign
Minister and current EU president Hans van Mierlo told a press
conference after the foreign ministers' informal meeting in The
Hague on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Mr Van Mierlo said the meeting had made some progress in
establishing the Union's Common Foreign and Security Policy(CFSP)
but acknowledged that difference remained on the issue of merging
the Western European Union(WEU) defense arm into the mainstream
EU.
</P>
<P>
EU heads of state and government are due to meet in the Dutch
seaside town of Noordwijk on Friday for an informal session to
give a final push for the Inter-Governmental Conference(IGC)
treaty review in order to have the IGC concluded successfully at
an Amsterdam summit on June 17-17.
</P>
<P>
Van Mierlo said that all member states had reacted positively
to an almost complete draft treaty prepared by The Netherlands,
but warned that a full draft would not be ready until early June.
</P>
<P>
"There is a degree of optimism that a positive result will be
achieved in Amsterdam," he said.
</P>
<P>
"But a great deal of work still needed to be done," he added,
referring particularly the strong opposition from Britain and the
four neutral state -- Ireland, Sweden, Austria and Finland, to the
EU-WEU merger.
</P>
<P>
The ministers have also discussed at the meeting how to
streamline the bloc's decision-making processes, diluting the
national veto with fewer areas requiring unanimity and
re-weighting the voting structure.
</P>
<P>
They agreed to strengthen the EU's procedure for agreeing
common foreign policies, with some member states suggesting that
the implementation of the Union's common foreign policies,
achieved by unanimity of the EU leaders, should be approved with
qualified-majority in the Council of Ministers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
