<HEADLINE> Britain to Launch Major Review of Live Animal Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 20 (Xinhua) -- Britain's new Labor government
announced here today that it would impose a major review of the
rules on exporting live animals to the other parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture minister Elliot Morley was quoted as saying in a
statement issued early today that the latest move reflected public
concern about the welfare of the animals and criticism about the
current arrangements.
</P>
<P>
Morley stressed in the statement: "Where animals are exported
live, the public must have full confidence that the strictest
possible welfare rules are being applied to this trade."
</P>
<P>
"Accordingly we have ordered an urgent review of the
arrangements for ensuring that animals are rested, fed, watered
and cleared as fit prior to export in accordance with the law," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He also made it clear that the government was planning to
implement new European Union rules on animal transit, including
limits on journey time, that were agreed in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
