<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ohio Professor Studies Impact of Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 20 (Xinhua) -- A Case Western Reserve
University study shows children are being exposed to alarmingly
high levels of violence and, as a result, are suffering severe
psychological trauma.
</P>
<P>
The study was conducted by Mark Singer, a professor of social
work, and involved 2,244 third- through eighth-graders in
Cleveland public schools and a number of rural schools in Ohio.
The results were presented Tuesday during a symposium sponsored by
the Ohio Department of Mental Health, The United Press
International reported.
</P>
<P>
Singer said children who witness violence or who are victims of
it are up to 10 times more likely to suffer psychological
problems.
</P>
<P>
Singer said psychologists and social workers must intervene
early in young people's lives to help them deal with problems
arising from violence.
</P>
<P>
He said, "Since school is the gathering place for children, it
should be one of the first places where responsible adults talk
with them about (violence)."
</P>
<P>
Singer said he found both boys and girls with the highest
exposure to violence suffered seriously elevated levels of
psychological trauma compared with those exposed to the least
violence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970521.0329 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profile: Kabila Fights for Idea of Congo for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Guo Ming)
</P>
<P>
KINSHASA, May 20 (Xinhua) -- Laurent Kabila, who has changed
the name of the central African country of Zaire to the
Democratic Republic of Congo and declared himself head of state
of of the republic, has fought for the idea of a self-relied
Congo for decades.
</P>
<P>
His arrival at capital Kinshasa tonight marked a final victory
over his long-time rival of Mobutu Sese Seko, who was toppled by
the Alliance of the Democratic Forces for the Liberation of
Congo-Zaire (LDFL) led by Kabila.
</P>
<P>
"My long years of struggle were like spreading fertilizer on a
field. But now it's time to harvest," said the strong, robust
rebel leader as he made a televised address to the nation on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Kabila, 56, heads the AFDL which was formed by four political
parties in the country. Its cutting edge is Banyamulenge ethnic
Tutsis who began the revolt in eastern Zaire in October 1996.
</P>
<P>
Known by followers as Mzee, the Swahili word for grand old
man, Kabila is the public point man for his alliance of four
political groups which was little known before formed on October
8, 1996 after they seized the first major eastern Zairean town of
Uvira.
</P>
<P>
They include the Popular Revolutionary Party (PRP) led by
Kabila himself, the National Council of Resistance for Democracy
(NCRD), the Revolutionary Movement for the Liberation of Zaire
(RMLZ), and the People's Democratic Alliance (PDA).
</P>
<P>
"The whole idea of our uprising is to form a new Congo which
has been devastated by the Mobutu regime," said Kabila's address
to the nation released on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"We should pursue self-reliance as our basic policy for
developing the Congo nation," he said.
</P>
<P>
It was Mobutu that gave the name of Zaire in 1965 when he came
to power following a military coup to topple the country's first
president Joseph Kasavubu.
</P>
<P>
A follower of Zaire's first Prime Minister Patrice Lumumba who
is passionate advocator of national unity regardless of ethnic
and regional differences, was murdered by secessionists under the
support of the United States.
</P>
<P>
It was also widely believed that Mobutu was behind Lumumba's
murder.
</P>
<P>
Although Kabila is from the mineral-rich Shaba Province in
southern Zaire, he has long been fighting against ethnicism and
regionalism in the country formed by over 250 ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
"I call for national unity of Congo," this sentence could
repeatedly heard from him.
</P>
<P>
Although he lived for many years among the Banyamulenge Tutsis
in the Mulenge mountains south of Uvira, from where he planned
the uprising, Kabila also traveled a lot and made friends with
many leaders both in Africa and in other parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
He staged three armed revolts in eastern Zaire. All were
crushed by Mobutu.
</P>
<P>
And 36 years after the assassination of Lumumber, Kabila
started his fourth uprising in October 1996 when he led the
Banyamulenge, a Tutsi community of roughly 400,000 people,
resisted attempts of the Zairean government to expel them to
Rwanda, a land they left up to 200 years ago.
</P>
<P>
This time, it took only seven months for Kabila, who had been
fighting Mobutu for three decades, to topple the Mobutu
government.
</P>
<P>
Well-educated, Kabila speaks perfect English despite coming
from Francophone Africa.
</P>
<P>
He is married with six children and one of them, Joseph, is
the alliance commander for the northern division which captured
the northeastern capital of Kisangani and southeast mineral
centre of Lubumbashi, Zaire's second largest city, and finally,
took over capital Kinshasa on May 17. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970521.0330 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Considers Trip to South Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 20 (Xinhua) -- Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright said on Tuesday that she was considering to visit South
Asia on the occasion of the 50th anniversary of the independence
of India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Before her talks with Pakistani Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub
Khan, Albright told reporters: "I am considering a trip to the
region. This is the 50th anniversary of independence and it seems
to be an appropriate time for a trip to be planned."
</P>
<P>
The secretary of state, however, did not give specific dates
for the possible trip.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan and India acquired independence in 1947 after Britain
ceded its colonial rule. But it created disputes over Kashmir,
leading to conflicts between India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Indian and Pakistani leaders held talks in Maldives
on the disputes over Kashmir and the talks were said to have been
successful by all accounts.
</P>
<P>
Albright said the meeting between the Indian and Pakistani
leaders were "very important and useful" in improving the two
countries' relations.
</P>
<P>
"We would consider it very important that a dialogue between
India and Pakistan about the subject would be very useful and
terrific to resolve this. From what we've heard there seems to
be some potential progress," she said.
</P>
<P>
Albright said she would be seeking a briefing from Ayub Khan
on the outcome of the meeting during her talks with the
Pakistani foreign minister. 
</P>
